<FIRST>r a AM-B-2-DefectivePart     08-26 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-2-Defective Part,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abbreviated Test Flight Blamed On Defective Part</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second test flight of
the B-2 stealth bomber was scrubbed in midflight because of a crack
in a part provided by a defense contractor once fined for billing
fraud, Air Force officials said.
   A hairline crack in a casing of an accessory drive, which powers
the $530 million high-tech jet's generators and controls, caused oil
pressure to drop during the Aug. 16 test flight, Air Force Capt.
Tess Taft said Thursday.
   ``It wasn't anything critical that would have caused the plane to
crash,'' she said. ``It was a minor problem.''
   The flight of the bat-wing bomber designed to pass through enemy
radar undetected was scheduled to last up to four hours, but was
halted after about one hour.
   The casing for the aircraft's No. 1 accessory drive was made by
Sundstrand Aviation of Rockford, Ill., which Pentagon officials
indefinitely suspended last year from doing business with the
government.
   Sundstrand was fined $115 million in October for overcharging the
government for parts, billing the Pentagon for baby-sitting costs,
country club dues and executive servants.
   The suspension did not affect contracts the company already had,
including the one for the B-2 casings.
   Sundstrand spokesman Claude Vernon said he would not comment on
the flaw.
   The part was redesigned to make it thicker after laboratory tests
indicated the casing would work better if strengthened, Ms. Taft
said.
   ``There's absolutely nothing wrong with the part as originally
designed,'' she said. ``Things break, OK?''
   Officials for Northrop Corp., which builds the B-2, said the
thinner casings, measuring four feet long, one foot wide and five
inches thick, were examined and cleared as airworthy.
   ``We wouldn't put anything in there that we thought was
potentially defective,'' said Northrop's B-2 spokesman Tony Cantafio.
   Air Force engineers continue to work with designers from
Northrop, Sundstrand and other subcontractors throughout the B-2
construction process and were fully aware of the modifications made
to thicken the casing, Ms. Taft said.
   Cantafio and Ms. Taft both said they were unaware of any plan to
replace the thinner parts before the B-2's next test flight.
   The government has spent about $22.4 billion in the B-2 program,
which is 18 months behind schedule, and Congress has balked at the
thought of paying more than $500 million apiece for 132 bombers.
   Shrouded in secrecy for 10 years, Northrop and the Pentagon last
month began an intensive campaign to surmount stealth foes.
   The Pentagon wants $4.7 billion for the bomber in the coming
fiscal year, and it may need $8 billion in each of the three years
of peak production, 1992 to 1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
