<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolClosings     08-26 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Closings,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Boston Can Close Five Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court ruled Friday that five Boston
public schools at the heart of a fierce dispute over budget-cutting
can be closed.
   Schools Superintendent Laval Wilson said the five schools will be
closed as planned and affected parents will receive new school
assignments for their children.
   On July 25, the city's school committee voted to close the
schools to meet Mayor Raymond Flynn's $362 million target budget and
to ease a projected $2.6 million deficit going into the school year.
   The three-judge Appeals Court panel ruled that the school
committee's vote was valid, even though it erred when a required
public hearing was delayed until Aug. 7.
   Parents who had fought the closings said they did not expect to
appeal Friday's decision, which overturned a Suffolk Superior Judge
David M. Roseman's decision Tuesday to block the closing plan.
   School Committee member Rob Cappucci said he preferred saving
money by closing the schools rather than putting special programs
like athletics ``on the chopping block.''
   ``I would rather close buildings than programs,'' said Cappucci.
   Wilson said the committee has made $3 million in administrative
staff cuts.
</TEXT>
