<DOCNO> AP890826-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-DrugLords     08-26 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Drug Lords,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Medieval-Style Castle Shows Drug Lords' Fast-Lane Philosophy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Why waltz when you can rock 'n' roll?''
wrote a visitor in the guest book at the medieval-style castle of
reputed cocaine trafficker Camilo Zapata Vasquez.
   The question reflects the fast-lane philosophy obviously embraced
by Colombia's wealthy drug lords, and was revealed in the public
confiscation of hundreds of their properties nationwide in an
anti-narcotics crackdown.
   The sandstone castle, ringed by formal gardens, dominates a
200-acre compound of 10 buildings, a dozen thoroughbred horses as
well as goats, ducks, dogs and even a couple of flamingos. Visible
from a nearby highway, it has long been a landmark in Chia, a suburb
13 miles north of Bogota.
   It was seized by the army this week, and shown off to reporters
on Friday.
   European and Oriential antiques filled the castle's richly
appointed rooms, lined with paintings, statues and ceramic
figurines. Beds were framed with crystal and bronze, or four
towering posters with marble bedside tables filled with electronics
to open and shut doors and control video equipment.
   A guest book provided a peek at the peculiar variety of people
who visited the estate.
   It is just one of many believed to have been owned by Zapata
Vasquez, even though he is considered a kind of second-string
smuggler, lacking the household-name stature of reputed cartel
bosses such as Pablo Escobar, Jorge Ochoa and Gonzalo Rodriguez
Gacha.
   The visitor who endorsed rock 'n' roll signed his message,
apparently in jest, ``M-19 power.'' M-19 is the name accorded to a
leftist guerrilla group operating in Colombia, although the
traffickers are much more closely associated with right-wing death
squads.
   Another visitor, calling himself Mad Max, wrote: ``Living by
chance, loving by choice and killing by profession.''
   An Oct. 10, 1988, visitor named Tuti wrote in a feminine hand:
``Happy birthday. Tomorrow they'll kill me and it'll be your fault.''
   Many women left their phone numbers after their signatures.
   Margarita Zapata, identified by army officials on the estate as
Zapata's sister, was much more solemn: ``May God and the Virgin
bless all of this and those who inhabit it.''
   The book also was signed by two men who identified themselves as
local police station commanders, two army lieutenants and an army
captain. Two local mayors also signed, one of them declaring, ``Few
people can truly appreciate the history of this property.''
   A group of women from several embassies, including Yugoslavia,
Uruguay, Chile, Canada and Britain signed the book, as did a tour
from a religious society.
   Next door to the estate is a religious boarding school run by
nuns.
   In a garage and sprawling servants' quarters attached to the
castle were two new Mercedes automobiles, also confiscated.
   There were also stables, where an office wall was lined with
ribbons and trophies; an indoor swimming pool and gym, tennis
courts, horse exercise trails and a modern thatch-roofed cottage of
many rooms.
   There was a chapel as well, dedicated to St. Francis of Assisi,
with stained glass windows, antique religious statues and pews for
about 30 people.
   Studiously ignoring the dozens of soldiers who guarded the place
were 10 groundskeepers who watered the well-kept lawns and acres of
gardens, trimmed the hundreds of yards of hedges and tended to the
animals.
   They gave contradicting statements about Zapata Vasquez: he never
came to stay, he came regularly, he just left a couple of weeks ago.
They all agreed on one thing: they were underpaid, receiving the
minimum legal wage _ about $80 a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890826-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Austria-Refugees Bjt   08-26 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Refugees, Bjt,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Europeans Get Help, but Pose Problems for Austria</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOERBISCH, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hospitality extended for 40 years
by this haven for Soviet bloc refugees is being strained as more
East Europeans take advantage of reforms and emigrate to the West.
   While East Germans flooding across the Austro-Hungarian border
this summer have enjoyed heartfelt welcomes, other East European
refugees find state support withering away.
   Women in the border town of Moerbisch have spent days sorting old
clothes, cooking and giving hugs to exhausted East Germans who
stumble in after a grueling journey to freedom through the
borderland brush.
   ``You just have to help. Anyone with a sense of humanity has
to,'' said one woman, her eyes filling with tears as she surveyed
the large hall where tables were piled high with clothes and dazed
East Germans sat over sausages and bread.
   ``I remember in 1956, my husband drove down to the border day and
night with his truck to pick up the refugees,'' she said on
condition of anonymity, recalling the mass exodus of Hungarians
after Soviet tanks crushed Hungary's anti-Stalinist uprising.
   In 1968, Austria sheltered streams of Czechoslovaks after other
Warsaw Pact countries crushed the ``Prague Spring'' reforms.
   And when martial law was declared in Poland in 1981, at least
35,000 Poles sought asylum here.
   Ilse Tremmel, chief organizer of Moerbisch's relief program, is
full of energy, seeing that volunteers get rest and giving a
mother's firm hug to a 17-year-old boy who left his childhood and
his parents on the other side of the East-West divide.
   ``The help has come from everywhere,'' she says. ``Private
individuals, companies, stores. Everyone is helping.''
   The East Germans spend only days in Austria before going to West
Germany.
   But thousands of Poles and Hungarians want to remain, and because
of that they feel less welcome.
   Their asylum applications now are rejected on grounds they are
not politically persecuted but seek only to improve their economic
situation.
   Refugee Peter Mojzer doesn't see the distinction. ``You can't
separate the two,'' he says. ``If the (communist) party regulates
everything, then you can't live or work freely.''
   Many Austrians believe the Hungarians and Poles sponge off the
state, receiving free room and board plus meager monthly allowances
while they wait years for applications to be processed.
   But in July and August, 3,800 Hungarians and Poles stopped
receiving the allowances and were turned out of government-rented
hotels and boarding houses.
   They came to Austria before May 1988, when the Austrian
government began rejecting most asylum applications.
   Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak, under fire from left-wingers
who argue this violates Austria's policy of sheltering all refugees,
insisted the Poles and Hungarians were informed months in advance.
But many said they were given only days' notice.
   About 800 jobs and language training for some Poles and
Hungarians was arranged to end the furor.
   But Austria, and the West in general, still faces the dilemma of
absorbing tens of thousands of East Europeans expected to cross
increasingly open borders.
   Pius Strobl, a leader of the small opposition Green-Alternative
party, noted that 10 percent of Austria's population of 7.4 million
are former refugees.
   Austria's declining population should encourage authorities to
integrate new arrivals who are anxious to work, he said.
   Two million refugees have come here since World War II ended and
613,000 remain, officials say. Last year, 16,000 applications for
asylum were submitted, double the number for 1986.
   Hungarians who refuse to return home and depend on charitable
organizations complain they are trapped in a Catch-22 situation _
needing a work permit to secure a residence permit, and a permanent
place of residence to acquire a work permit.
   ``Who can guarantee that the reforms in Hungary will continue,''
asked Ferenc Briski, who came to Austria in 1987.
   Briski's family is among several that found lodging in eastern
Burgenland province with help from the Greens and charity groups.
Some live without electricity or heating.
   Hungarian-born Wilma Csoknyai recalls when she came to Austria
after World War II and how impressed she was with the hospitality.
   ``After the war, when nobody had anything, it was apparently
easier to be a refugee,'' she said. ``Now people can't imagine how
it is to have nothing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
