university professor, according to news reports today.
   The reports, quoting palace and government officials it did not
name, followed months of speculation that the prince and Kiko
Kawashima, a graduate student at Tokyo's Gakushuin University, were
making marriage plans.
   The reports were carried by the mass-circulation Asahi Shimbun
newspaper, Kyodo News Service and on the Japan Broadcasting Corp.'s
morning news.
   Prince Aya, 23, is a student of zoology at St. John's College,
Oxford, and is home in Japan for a short vacation. He is to return
to England Sept. 20.
   Aya is second in line to the throne, which his father assumed
Jan. 7 after the death of Emperor Hirohito.
   The engagement must still be approved by the 10-member Imperial
Council, headed by Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu.
   Plans for Aya's marriage could be delayed because his elder
brother, Crown Prince Naruhito, has yet to settle on a bride.
Naruhito, 29, reportedly hopes to marry within the next year or so.
