<FIRST>r a PM-Voyager-Quayle     08-26 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Quayle,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Signals Interest in Space Program With Visit to NASA Lab</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Voyager-Neptune, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle visited NASA's
Jet Propulsion Laboratory to congratulate Voyager scientists and
underscore his new interest in the U.S. space program.
   ``I am exceedingly delighted to be here on this very historic day
for America and America's space program,'' Quayle told a receptive
crowd of perhaps 1,000 laboratory employees.
   The crowd cheered as Quayle said that unmanned missions _ the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory's specialty _ will continue to be an important
part of the U.S. space program.
   ``We are seeing a beginning of a new era where we'll see a
recommitment to space,'' Quayle said, echoing comments he has made
in recent months as he works hard to adopt the space program as his
issue.
   Quayle's visit Friday morning followed Voyager 2's close
encounter with Neptune that capped a 12-year, 4.4 billion-mile
flight that took the two Voyager spacecraft to Jupiter in 1979,
Saturn in 1980 and 1981, and Uranus in 1986.
   Quayle, who had shown little interest in the space program before
becoming vice president, has now seized upon it as an issue he can
use to improve his political fortunes.
   ``It's a great opportunity for him, because ordinarily vice
presidents have limited duties,'' said David Beckwith, Quayle's
press secretary.
   The issue was handed to Quayle by Congress, which established the
National Space Council at the end of the Reagan administration and
designated the vice president as its head.
   Quayle is hoping to convince Congress and the public that
expenditures on space are worthwhile, even in the face of continuing
federal budget deficits.
   On July 20, the 20-year anniversary of the landing of a man on
the moon, President Bush called for the permanent settlement of
space, by first returning to the moon and then sending a manned
mission to Mars.
   Bush charged NASA and Quayle, as head of the National Space
Council, with developing a plan to carry out those goals. The plan
is supposed to be delivered to Bush in October.
   Quayle's visit to the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, which included a
briefing with laboratory officials and a tour of the Voyager control
center, was patterned after a successful visit last month to the
General Dynamics Space systems division is San Diego.
   Quayle gave the same stump speech in both places, contending that
space exploration furthers scientific understanding, provides jobs,
leads to new technology and inspires young people to seek careers in
science or engineering.
</TEXT>
