<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cara and Neil Murphy were excited
about getting a new baby brother, but sitting in a hospital waiting
for him to come wasn't a fun way to spend their birthday.
   A little assurance from Dad helped ease the conflict of having a
third Murphy born Aug. 22.
   ``We've always been careful about keeping the birthdays
individual,'' said the children's father, Rod Murphy. ``From now on,
it'll be three cakes at our house every August 22nd.''
   Cara turned 10 Tuesday and Neil turned 7. And Thomas Andrew
Murphy was born.
   ``I've been taking a lot of ribbing at work,'' their father said.
``They're asking me if we're going for a world record.''
   To do that, Rod and his wife, Kathy, will have to come up with
three more children born on Aug. 22.
   The Guinness Book of World Records, under the category
``Coincidental Birth Dates,'' reports that Carolyn Cummins, of
Clintwood, Va., gave birth to five children on five different Feb.
20ths from 1952 through 1966.
   Still, the odds against coming up with a triple birthday,
according to a Michigan State University statistician, are 100,000
to one.
   Thomas Andrew came three days late and weighed 9{ pounds.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLEN ELLYN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now, for the parents with everything _
Rent-A-Stork.
   The $50, 6-foot wooden bird can perch outside the front door with
a pink or blue bundle in its beak _ just the thing to announce a new
birth to your neighbors.
   Rent-A-Stork, along with computerized fairy tales, children's
compact discs and diaper delivery services that also deliver meals,
was among about 75 exhibits at the Midwest Baby and Kids Expo this
week.
   Diane Doessel of Diane's Personalized Children's Books was
printing up stories by computer on the spot, exchanging the names of
children who stepped up to her exhibit booth for those of the
stories' heroes.
   ``Kids love to be the star of their own stories,'' she said. The
books cost $8.95.
