<FIRST>r a PM-Bush Bjt   08-26 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges Other Nations to Support Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XKNE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, appealing to other
nations to rally behind Colombian officials ``on the front line of
the war against drugs,'' is sending President Virgilio Barco's
government a $65 million package to combat narcotics trafficking.
   The aid announced Friday by the summer White House consists
primarily of aircraft _ mostly helicopters _ and a variety of other
equipment and supplies, but no U.S. troops.
   However, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said some U.S.
advisers would be sent to show Colombians how to use and maintain
the equipment. He said they would number fewer than ``dozens'' but
did not have a precise figure.
   ``We will provide only material support and training,'' the
vacationing president said in a statement. ``The United States has
complete confidence in the capability of the Colombian police and
military to deal with this situation.
   ``It is time for the United States and other countries of the
world to stand with President Barco during his courageous challenge
to these insidious forces that threaten the very fabric of Colombian
society.''
   Bush vowed ``to assist the Colombian officials who are on the
front line of the war against drugs.''
   Colombia has been rocked by recent drug-related violence,
including the assassination last week of the leading presidential
candidate and this week's bombings of homes and offices of
government and political leaders.
   Fitzwater said eight Huey transport helicopters would be sent to
Columbia next week, and another 12 would be sent later along with a
Blackhawk helicopter for medical evacuation.
   A U.S. Air Force C-5 transport plane brought in two Bell 212
helicopters Friday that were delivered to Colombian authorities. The
helicopters, which add to six of the same type Colombian police
already had, represent ``an immediate, tangible response of the U.S.
government to President Barco's stepped-up war on the narcotics
traffic,'' the U.S. Embassy said in a statement.
   Fitzwater said the eight Hueys would be used mainly ``for
carrying troops and policemen into rural areas'' and for locating
drug activity.
   In addition, another 20 helicopters previously bought by
Colombia, and not part of the new package, will also be shipped over
the next few months, Fitzwater said.
   The package includes another $8.6 million for light aircraft, but
the type and number has yet to be determined, Fitzwater said.
   Also in the package are machine guns and other small arms,
grenade launchers, mortars, aircraft ammunition, radios, jeeps,
ambulances, field gear, anti-tank weapons, field trucks, utility
boats, 18-man ``assault boats'' that carry machine guns, medical
supplies, tools and spare parts.
   Bush's statement reiterated the administration's vow to work with
Colombian legal officials in extraditing drug traffickers wanted in
the United States.
   Fitzwater said the overall package ``represents a conclusion that
we have a responsibility and an interest in helping them to the
maximum degree possible.''
   The aircraft and supplies will help Barco ``launch a major
effort'' against the drug cartel, Fitzwater said.
   The money comes from a special foreign aid fund and is separate
from Bush's new $8 billion anti-drug program to be unveiled by the
president in a nationally televised address Sept. 5. Fitzwater said
the drug at plan will also contain additional funds for Colombia and
other Latin American countries.
   The money is also separate from a $2 million program announced
earlier in the week to help Colombia set up security for public
officials.
   Bush will meet with Cabinet members involved in drug policy and
drug-policy coordinator William Bennett here next week.
   The president is midway through a three-week vacation that runs
through Labor Day. Evangelist Billy Graham was spending the weekend
with the first family.
   Bush on Friday followed what has been his usual pattern of
athletic activities, including golf, boating and horseshoes.
   At one point, Bush ran his 28-foot speedboat, Fidelity, into a
hard submerged object _ either a rock or piece of wood _ forcing him
to abandon a morning of boating.
   However, the mishap, which damaged the housing of one of his
propellers, was quickly repaired by a local marina and Bush was back
on the water by late afternoon.
</TEXT>
