<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0301EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-LeningradLibrary     08-26 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leningrad Library,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release at noon EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Library of Congress to Combat Damage in Leningrad's Great Collection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Library of Congress said today it has
received $135,000 to help restore fire- and water-damaged books in a
Leningrad institution where one of the worst library disasters in
history occurred.
   The gift from Reader's Digest will help experts counter the
damage at the USSR Academy of Sciences Library, whose collection of
20 million books, manuscripts and periodicals was begun in 1714 by
Peter the Great.
   Four million books were damaged or destroyed in a 19-hour fire in
February 1988.
   The Library of Congress is a leader in developing techniques to
rescue books threatened by decay or disaster.
   James H. Billington, librarian of Congress and a Russian expert,
went to Leningrad after the fire to assess the damage and arranged
for a protocol, signed by the two institutions, agreeing to preserve
damaged materials and replace destroyed books.
   Peter Waters, a Library of Congress expert on the conservation of
damaged book collections, went to Leningrad within six weeks of the
fire.
   Billington welcomed the gift, saying in a statement that it
underscored the principle that library collections ``are truly
international resources for humanity which all of us must support
whenever one of them is threatened by destruction.''
   The library said the Reader's Digest grant will finance
equipment, supplies and technical consultation to return to use many
of the 200,000 rare volumes that were frozen in an effort to arrest
deterioration after the fire.
   The Leningrad institution is one of the world's largest research
libraries, although not nearly as large as the Library of Congress,
which holds 86 million items.
   The Academy Library is a major exchange partner for most U.S.
research libraries that collect Russian and Soviet materials. Every
year, several hundred U.S. specialists in Russians affairs visit
there to do research.
   A few months after the fire, Soviet historian and cultural
activist Dmitri Likhachev said the disaster could have been
prevented if officials had heeded warnings about the dilapidated
condition of the Soviet Union's most prestigious book collections.
   He said it pained him to see how rare books and art treasures
that were spirited away by residents of Leningrad to protect them
from Nazis who occupied the city in World War II had been destroyed
through negligence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890826-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Congressman-Prostitute Bjt   08-26 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressman-Prostitute, Bjt,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barney Frank Says Disclosure He Hired Prostitute Won't Cripple Career</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Barney Frank says his political
career is intact but he made a big mistake in hiring a paroled male
prostitute to do personal chores at his Washington home.
   Frank, who disclosed his homosexuality in May 1987, befriended
and employed the man four years ago after paying him for sex. The
Massachusetts Democrat fired his employee in August 1987 when he
suspected the man was selling sex from Frank's apartment.
   ``Certainly if I were a voter, I would not ask my advice on how
to rehabilitate someone,'' Frank, 49, said during a news conference
Friday at his office in this Boston suburb. ``I think I have had
much better judgment in my public life.''
   The state Republican Party called on Frank to resign, but the
congressman, up for re-election in 1990, said the incident would not
affect his political career or plans.
   ``I don't think I'm going to be heavily penalized by the voters
for being suckered by a guy I was trying to help,'' he said.
   Some of his colleagues agreed.
   House Speaker Tom Foley, a Democrat, said Frank ``has provided
outstanding service to his constituency and the nation, and I am
absolutely confident he will continue to do so long after this
matter has been forgotten.''
   The only other member of Congress to acknowledge being
homosexual, Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., easily won re-election after
being censured by the House in 1983 for an affair 10 years earlier
with a 17-year-old House page.
   After revealing his homosexuality, Frank won election to his
fifth term in 1988 with 70 percent of the vote in the state's 4th
District, which encompasses some Boston suburbs and parts of
southeastern Massachusetts.
   ``Barney Frank is on virtually everyone's list as one of the 10
ablest members of Congress,'' Studds said. ``I suspect he will
remain on that list for a very long time to come.''
   Frank's hiring of the male prostitute was first detailed in
Friday's editions of The Washington Times.
   The newspaper said the man was named Greg Davis, but Frank said
his real name is Steve Gobie. No telephone number was listed for a
Steve Gobie in Washington or its suburbs.
   Frank said he met the man in 1985, and estimated his age at 26 or
27. The congressman admitted paying for sex with the man once, but
said the relationship quickly became one of friendship.
   He said he paid Gobie to do household chores, driving and other
errands from his own money, not congressional or campaign funds. The
total compensation amounted to about $20,000 a year, including cash
and payment of lawyer and other bills.
   In an interview on WUSA-TV in Washington, D.C., a man identifying
himself as Gobie repeated charges that Frank was aware of the sexual
activities at the apartment.
   ``He knew what was taking place. He knew there were clients
coming to his house. As long as the clients weren't there when he
was there, that was no problem,'' Gobie said.
   Frank called the man's allegations that he was aware of the
activity ``absolutely untrue.''
   Alexander Tennant, executive director of the state GOP, said
Frank should resign because there are laws against patronizing
prostitutes.
   ``This is simply a question of a congressman who had the public's
trust and violated this trust by engaging in illegal activity,''
Tennant said. ``Frank revealed today that he paid for sex.''
   Frank said his only other contact with Gobie, after the firing in
August 1987, came in December of that year when Gobie called to say
he was having problems and needed help.
   At the hourlong news conference, Frank refused to answer most
questions about his sex life. But he did say the temptation to pay
for sex was ``one of the things that led me to acknowledge being
gay. ... It was one of the reasons I was vulnerable to being preyed
on.''
   He told The Associated Press that he has now been in a monogamous
relationship for about two years with ``a very sensible person and a
steadying influence.''
</TEXT>
