<FIRST>r w PM-SoybeanCorner Bjt   08-26 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybean Corner, Bjt,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Sees No Conflict in CBOT Soybean Emergency; Senator Skeptical</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RETRANSMITTING to add budget designator.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee says a report by federal regulators raises
conflict-of-interest questions regarding the activities of Chicago
Board of Trade officials during last month's soybean emergency.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which oversees the
nation's futures markets, said Friday that an initial review of the
emergency liquidation in the soybean futures market found no
examples of self-dealing.
   But Sen. Patrick Leahy, the Agriculture Committee chairman, noted
the report raised possible conflict-of-interest questions about
several of the officials who voted for the forced reduction of
holdings in July soybean futures contracts.
   ``The CFTC must question those Chicago Board of Trade directors
participating in the July soybean decision whose affiliated firms
held net short positions in the July soybean contract in house or
customer accounts,'' said Leahy, D-Vt., in a statement issued by his
office.
   Futures contracts are agreements to deliver a quantity of goods
at a specified price at a certain time in the future.
   ``Credibility is paramount for exchanges in carrying out their
self-regulatory functions. The public will not tolerate self-dealing
or conflict of interest by exchange directors or insiders,'' Leahy
said.
   The Board of Trade, the world's largest commodity exchange,
issued an emergency order last month requiring traders to reduce
their holdings in soybean futures contracts.
   That decision touched off wild swings in soybean prices and
sparked sharp criticism by farm groups, and traders saw the value of
their futures holdings drop.
   Those who had sold borrowed soybean futures on speculation the
price would fall, in what's known as a short position, stood to gain
from the emergency order because it resulted in a steep drop in
soybean prices.
   The Board of Trade has said it took the action after consulting
with the CFTC, because a subsidiary of Italian grain merchant
Ferruzzi Finanziaria S.P.A., failed to voluntarily reduce its large
holdings in the July soybean market.
   CBOT officials have said the exchange was worried that soybean
supplies were insufficient for meeting large holdings of contracts
for July delivery of soybeans in the final days of trading in that
contract.
   The July 11 order requiring traders to reduce their positions in
the July soybean market to 1 million bushels was widely perceived as
a move to prevent Ferruzzi from cornering the soybean market, which
Ferruzzi has denied.
   Ferruzzi also has bitterly criticized the CBOT action.
   ``We continue to believe that is was totally unnecessary for the
board to take its emergency action,'' said David Swanson, an
executive with Ferruzzi Group, a U.S. subsidiary.
   ``The Ferruzzi Group supports Sen. Leahy's call for further
investigation by the CFTC into the matter,'' said Swanson, also
chief executive officer of Central Soya Co.
   The CFTC's preliminary report was contained in a 36-page letter
to Leahy from CFTC Chairwoman Wendy L. Gramm.
   Among the preliminary findings, the CFTC's review disclosed no
Board of Trade governing member appeared to trade for the purpose of
profiting personally, or through an affiliated company, from prior
knowledge of the July 11 order.
   ``Our position is that even though a firm held a position (in the
July soybean market) a director would not be influenced,'' said BOT
spokesman Michael Oakes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
