<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SevenWonders     08-26 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seven Wonders,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Seven Underwater Wonders of World' Are Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of marine experts says the ``seven
underwater wonders of the world'' could be lost without a global
effort to protect the world's oceans and seas.
   ``We're killing the oceans,'' said former astronaut Scott
Carpenter, one of a panel of experts who named the sites Friday to
focus public attention on the world's underwater environment.
   Rick Sammon, president of the sponsoring organization, CEDAM
International, said the selection was the start of an educational
campaign aimed at preserving ``the world's beautiful but very
fragile marine environment.''
   ``If a concerted effort is not undertaken soon to protect and
preserve our underwater wonders, they _ like the classic Seven
Wonders of the World _ could be lost forever through carelessness,
negligence or deliberate mistreatment,'' he said.
   The seven underwater wonders, selected by the 14-member panel of
marine scientists, conservationists and explorers, are:
   Palau, an island group in Micronesia; the northern Red Sea; the
Great Barrier Reef of Australia; the waters of the Galapagos Islands
off the coast of Ecuador; Lake Baikal in Siberia; the Belize Barrier
Reef; and the deep ocean vents in the middle of the Atlantic and
Pacific oceans.
   An honorable mention went to whales as one of the great living
wonders of the seas.
   CEDAM International is a non-profit group of 1,000 mostly marine
scientists and conservationists based at Croton-on-Hudson, N.Y.
   The educational campaign will include collecting data and
publishing information packets about the seven sites, a documentary
series, a touring exhibit of underwater photographs, school
curricula on marine conservation and an art-quality photo book.
   Carpenter, an environmental consultant from Vail, Colo., blamed
the world's runaway population for the declining health of the
oceans and marine life.
   ``We've got to stop population growth and we've got to eliminate
our ignorance,'' he said.
   ``The ocean is a very delicate entity and people don't realize
that. Without healthy oceans, a healthy planet is impossible.''
   The 13 other panelists included representatives of the
Smithsonian Institution, the National Geographic Society, the United
Nations, the New York Aquarium, the New York Zoological Society,
Wildlife Conservation International, the University of Maryland, the
federal National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and CSIRO,
Australia's largest scientific and industrial research organization.
</TEXT>
