<FIRST>r a PM-IvyLeagueTrial     08-26 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ivy League Trial,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Harvard Student Sentenced for Armed Robberies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man from a poor, Hispanic
neighborhood who went on to attend Harvard University was sentenced
to 10 years in prison for six armed robberies committed during
school breaks.
   Jose Luis Razo, 22, was convicted in June of six robberies and
attempting to escape police after his 1987 arrest in Orange County.
He was found innocent of four other robberies.
   ``He's earned his way to Harvard, but he also earned his way to
prison,'' Deputy District Attorney Ravi Mehta told the court before
sentencing. ``Mr. Razo needs to pay his dues to society now. Mr.
Razo needs to be punished for what he's done.''
   Razo also faces trial in Los Angeles County, where he is charged
with three counts of robbery and six of assault with a deadly weapon.
   ``I have not disregarded the good things I have learned about
you, Mr. Razo,'' Orange County Superior Court Judge Jean Rheinheimer
said before she sentenced Razo on Friday. ``This is not a happy
sentencing for this court.''
   Rheinheimer, who could have given him a maximum 15-year term, was
asked by the defense to consider Razo's achievements as a star
athlete and scholar who gave time to charity.
   ``I don't know how it is that a boy such as Jose Razo stands
before this court facing 15 years in state prison,'' said attorney
John Barnett. ``Perhaps the gap between the barrio of La Habra and
Harvard University was just too wide for him to pass.''
   But Rheinheimer said she could not ignore the fact the crimes
were premeditated and occurred over a two-year period, showing what
she called a ``pattern of conduct dangerous to society.''
   Each of the 10 store robberies, committed between December 1985
and June 1987, occurred during school breaks while he attended
Harvard for two years.
   Razo sat expressionless Friday as the sentence was read. His
tearful parents refused to comment. ``What can we say?'' Jose Razo
Sr. said.
   Barnett said he planned an appeal.
   He called the sentence too severe, but added, ``The judge gave
her honest opinion of what the crimes were worth and what the
defendant was worth.''
   With credit for time served and for good behavior, Razo could be
eligible for release in about three years, Mehta said outside court.
Razo will then face three years on parole. A $500 fine also was
imposed.
   Razo was a former high school football star, Boys Club ``Boy of
the Year'' and outstanding student at Servite Roman Catholic High
School in Anaheim.
   The prosecution's case relied heavily on a videotaped confession
in which Razo recounted with vivid detail the crimes, each committed
by a gunman wearing a ski mask. The holdups at fast-food
restaurants, grocery and drug stores, netted the gunman $27,000.
   Razo later retracted the confession, saying he was in a
drug-induced stupor. He claimed he was describing crimes actually
committed by a friend.
</TEXT>
