<FIRST>r w PM-AsianBases     08-26 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Asian Bases,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schroeder Says Philippines Shouldn't Expect Large Sums of U.S. Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Schroeder, the Colorado Democrat who
heads the panel that funds U.S. military bases, says the Philippines
will have ``a long wait coming'' if they expect large sums of U.S.
aid.
   Her comments came as the United States and the Philippines
prepare to start negotiations on renewing six military base leases
that expire in 1991. Many Filipino lawmakers are demanding far
higher U.S. aid in return, or a phased withdrawal of American forces.
   Schroeder, just back from a 16-day trip to Japan, the
Philippines, Taiwan, Thailand and South Korea, said the Philippines
wants $2 billion each year.
   ``I told them that if they are waiting for foreign aid to more
than double, they have a long wait coming,'' she said in a statement
Friday.
   Her sentiments have been echoed in recent weeks by other
lawmakers visiting the region over the summer recess.
   The United States agreed to pay the Philippines some $960 million
until 1991, but Schroeder said she would introduce a bill to sever
the link between U.S. foreign aid for the Philippines and U.S. base
rights there.
   ``Either a base is necessary for mutual defense or it is not,''
she said.
   Schroeder also issued a report she commissioned from the General
Accounting Office, the watchdog agency of Congress, which said Japan
could save the United States $600 million annually by assuming
payments in Japanese yen for such things as utility bills and
salaries of Japanese workers on the bases.
   The report also disputed Japan's claim that it cannot increase
support for U.S. forces without renegotiating the 1960 agreement for
the stationing of American troops there.
   ``The Japanese are hiding behind this document, and our
government lets them get away with it,'' Schroeder said.
   The study praised Japan for increasing its share of funding for
the U.S. forces from 24 percent in 1981 to 31 percent or $1.7
billion in 1987. But it said much of the gain resulted from the fact
that the stronger yen now buys more dollars.
   ``Although the increase in Japanese support from 1981 to 1987 is
impressive when measured in U.S. dollars, much of it can be
attributed to the decline of the dollar's value against the yen,''
the report said.
   When measured in dollars, Japan's cash contributions rose 137
percent, but because of the strengthening of the yen, the actual
increase was 44 percent, the study found.
</TEXT>
