<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Pledges To Seek More U.S. Aid for to Rebuild Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole says he'll
seek increased American aid for reconstruction in earthquake-damaged
Soviet Armenia.
   The Kansas Republican, according to a statement released by his
office here Friday, made the pledge in Poland after he and his wife,
Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole, toured the damaged areas in Armenia
and delivered $50,000 worth of relief supplies.
   The supplies were gathered by Project Hope, a private U.S. relief
agency.
   The U.S. government has provided $4 million worth of assistance,
most of it in transportation, since the Dec. 7 earthquake that
killed 25,000 people. Americans have given another $160 million
privately, Dole said.
   ``If anybody wants to look at a place where they could use help _
whether they're children, whether they're schools, whether they're
homes _ here's a little country of 3.3 million people with 700,000
homeless,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. Urges Cease-Fire in Angola</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is urging warring
Angolan factions to reach a cease-fire to end the outbreak of
violence in the civil war there.
   ``In order for there to be an effective cease-fire, there must be
a comprehensive cease-fire agreement. Such an agreement would be in
the interest of both sides,'' State Department spokesman Richard
Boucher said Friday.
   Angola's UNITA guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi on Thursday
renounced a truce that began in June. The agreement between Savimbi
and Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos was designed to end
the 14-year civil war.
   The truce began collapsing the week after it began. UNITA said
Friday that 77 government troops and six of its rebels were killed
in heavy fighting this week.
   F.W. de Klerk, South Africa's acting president, and Zaire's
President Mobutu Sese Seko agreed at a summit meeting Friday in
Goma, Zaire, to cooperate in trying to salvage the Angolan peace
agreement.
   Mobutu has been spearheading efforts to negotiate a settlement of
Angola's civil war, and South Africa has endorsed his initiative
after ending its material support for UNITA.
   Boucher said the United States was urging Angolan factions ``to
resume negotiations under Zairean mediation'' to reach a cease-fire
agreement.
   Western-backed UNITA, the Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, has been fighting the
government and its Cuban allies to force a power-sharing agreement
since shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Severe Cold Harms Projected Hazelnut Harvest</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's filbert harvest in Oregon and
Washington is estimated at 13,500 tons, down 18 percent from 1988
and the smallest output since 1984, the Agriculture Department says.
   The Oregon crop of filberts, or hazelnuts, was forecast at 13,300
tons, compared with 16,300 tons in 1988. The Washington harvest was
indicated at 200 tons, the same as last year.
   Officials said filbert trees, particularly of the Barcelona
variety, were hurt by severe cold in early February during their
crucial pollination stage.
   ``As a result, nut set is lighter than in 1988,'' said Friday's
report. ``Also, growers report a larger-than-normal number of
blanks. Nut size, however, is up significantly from last year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
