<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Contras Bjt   08-26 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Contras, Bjt,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contra Forces to be Disbanded Starting Sept. 6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After eight years of guerrilla war, the
U.S.-backed Contra rebels who fought to topple Nicaragua's
Sandinista government will begin disbanding in less than two weeks.
   The secretary-general of the Organization of American States,
Joao Clemente Baena Soares of Brazil, and U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar announced Friday that work will begin Sept.
6.
   Perez de Cuellar met with Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Miguel
d'Escoto Brockmann to discuss resettling the estimated 11,000 to
12,000 Nicaraguan rebels, now based in Honduras.
   Upon learning that dates had been fixed for the demobilization of
the Contras, d'Escoto said: ``That is very good news; we have wanted
that for a very long time.
   ``I would imagine that the vast majority of the people would want
to come home. Even some of the Miami contras have returned,'' said
d'Escoto.
   Under an agreement signed Aug. 7 by the presidents of Nicaragua,
El Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala, the U.S.-supported
Contras are to repatriated or resettled in other countries.
   The Tela Declaration calls for the rebels to be resettled by Dec.
5.
   Numerous Contra field commanders and guerrillas have said they
will not give up their fight.
   However, a U.N. diplomat active in Central American affairs said
preliminary talks with the rebels indicate they are quite willing to
go home or be resettled, and that little resistance is expected.
   Disarming and resettling the Contras will require a new U.N.
peacekeeping force, said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The world body's experts believe the size and cost of such a
force can be minimized if the Contras are disarmed over a period of
months in small groups, rather than rounded up and disarmed at once,
he said.
   The United States had lobbied the Central American nations to
allow the Contras to stay in their border camps in Honduras until
national elections are held in Nicaragua on Feb. 25, to maintain
pressure on the Sandinistas to allow a fair campaign.
   Even Honduras, however, which has received lavish military and
foreign aid from Washington, agreed earlier this month that there
was no justification to allow the Contras to remain until then.
   The United States gives the Contras $4.5 million a month in
non-lethal aid, which may also be used for resettlement.
   Congress cut off money for weapons last year. The Contras later
negotiated a truce with the Sandinistas and since then have launched
only sporadic raids.
   Perez de Cuellar also met Friday with El Salvador's foreign
minister, Jose Manuel Pacas Castro.
   El Salvador wants its Central American neighbors to turn their
attention on disbanding the leftist rebel force trying to topple its
government, a goal the U.S. government shares.
   The joint U.N.-OAS statement alluded to that aim by saying
efforts will be made to disband and resettle ``all those involved in
armed actions in the countries of the region when they voluntarily
seek it.''
   The Salvadoran rebels are the Faribundo Marti Liberation Front,
known by its Spanish acronym as the FMLN.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
