<HEAD>Frank is 4th Congressman Touched by Sex Allegations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Congressman-Prostitute Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., is the fourth
member of Congress to make news this year because of sexual
activities _ or alleged attempted activities.
   The House ethics committee already is investigating three
members. But there is no indication that Frank's admission Friday
that a male prostitute operated out of his Washington home for a
time would trigger an investigation.
   The three members under investigations authorized earlier this
month are Reps. Gus Savage, D-Ill.; Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens,
R-Ohio; and Jim Bates, D-Calif.
   According to news accounts, Savage fondled a Peace Corps worker
during a trip to Zaire. Savage, who is black, says the incident was
misrepresented and has called on his Chicago constituents to boycott
white-owned media outlets there.
   Lukens is appealing a $1,000 fine and 180-day jail sentence in
Ohio for conviction on a misdemeanor charge of contributing to the
unruliness of a minor. A girl accused him of having sex with her
when she was 16.
   Bates has been charged with sexual harassment by two women who
worked on his staff. He has denied the accusations.
