<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrikes     08-26 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strikes,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Back to Bargaining Table for Striking Telephone Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NYNEX Corp. and its striking telephone workers
agreed to go back to the bargaining table for the first formal talks
since a walkout started almost three weeks ago.
   In a terse statement Friday, NYNEX said both sides had agreed to
resume talking Wednesday to ``negotiate all items in the contract,
including the health care issue.''
   Employee contributions to health-insurance plans have been a
major issue in the Aug. 6 strike by more than 60,000 workers in New
York and New England.
   Nationally, 200,000 workers in 20 states struck. But union
leaders have negotiated settlements with striking employees at
Pacific Telesis, which serves Caifornia and Nevada; most of
Chicago-based Ameritech, which serves five Midwest states; and Bell
Atlantic in West Virginia, Virginia, Maryland, Delaware,
Pennsylvania and Washington, D.C., but not in New Jersey.
   Communications Workers of America vice president Jan Pierce
announced Thursday that his union was increasing harassment tactics
to get NYNEX to the bargaining table. Hours later, several hundred
CWA pickets demonstrated outside the suburban home of NYNEX
president William Ferguson.
   NYNEX spokesman John Bonomo said Friday that the return to
negotiations resulted from ``simply good faith, no particular
reason.''
   In addition to talks between the CWA and NYNEX in Rye, north of
New York City, representatives of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers in New England were to resume talks with company
officials in Boston Wednesday.
</TEXT>
