<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Korea     08-26 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indicted Opposition Leader to Launch Anti-Government Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INCHON, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the largest opposition
party, under indictment in connection with a spy case, said today he
is launching a campaign to get his prosecutor fired and to force the
government to expedite reform.
   Kim Dae-jung, head of the Party for Peace and Democracy, said it
will battle the government in the National Assembly, the courts and
among the people to speed democratic reforms and wipe out legacies
of past authoritarian regimes.
   ``There are over 900 political prisoners in jail. This is more
than were jailed at any one time under the Chun Doo-hwan regime,''
he said, referring to the predecessor of President Roh Tae-woo.
   Speaking at a news conference prior to a rally in the western
port of Inchon, Kim said the indictment against him ``is tantamount
to the government of Roh Tae-woo declaring it has given up its
willingness to carry out reforms toward democracy.''
   Kim and two members of his party were indicted Friday for failing
to report the illegal visit to North Korea by National Assemblyman
Suh Kyung-won.
   Suh has been jailed on charges of violating national security
laws, espionage and accepting $120,000 from communist agents. He
surrendered to authorities June 25 and was formally charged and
expelled from the party three days later for a trip made in August
1988.
   National security laws forbid unauthorized travel to communist
North Korea, which South Korea has considered an enemy since the
peninsula was divided in 1945. The two Koreas fought a war in
1950-53, but a peace treaty was never signed.
   Kim, who ran for president in 1971 and 1987, has denied he had
prior knowledge of Suh's trip or espionage, and says the government
has purposely harassed the opposition party to discredit and
embarrass it among voters.
   He said his party will introduce a resolution in the National
Assembly seeking the dismissal of Prosecutor General Kim Ki-chun, in
charge of investigating the case, and will call for televised
hearings on democratic reform.
   In September, he said, the party will begin a nationwide petition
drive to press demands for democratization and will hold rallies in
27 cities to denounce political suppression.
   Kim charged that ``tortures are practiced widely even though the
constitution guarantees the rights of suspects to be assisted by
counsel.'' Kim claimed Suh had been physically tortured for 50 days
by being allowed to sleep only in brief intervals and enduring
interrogations standing.
   He said others have had to endure similar torture.
</TEXT>
