<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-PrisonReading     08-26 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Prison Reading,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Do Inmates in KGB Prison Read? Gorbachev's Writings, Paper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The works of Mikhail S. Gorbachev are popular with
at least one captive audience _ inmates at the KGB's Lefortovo
Prison, a newspaper said.
   ``There is much interest in political developments taking place
in the country,'' the government daily Izvestia reported Friday. It
said inmates at the eastern Moscow prison _ whose cells have housed
U2 pilot Francis Gary Powers and West German daredevil flier Mathias
Rust _ are ``avid'' readers of the Soviet president's writings and
speeches.
   Also popular are speeches and documents from last year's national
Communist Party conference and the inaugural session of the
country's new parliament, the Congress of People's Deputies,
Izvestia said. Participants in those meetings scathingly criticized
Soviet problems, and some even called for legal checks on the state
agency that runs Lefortovo, the KGB secret police.
   Gorbachev may soon have competition for readers behind bars,
however.
   Izvestia noted inmates will soon be able to read Alexander
Solzhenitsyn's ``Gulag Archipelago,'' an expose of the cruelties of
the Soviet prison and labor camp system since the days of Lenin.
</TEXT>
