<FIRST>r a PM-NewtonKilled Bjt   08-26 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newton Killed, Bjt,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Dealer Arrested in Black Panther Co-Founder's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX4 of Aug. 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police believe the killing of Black
Panther co-founder Huey P. Newton was an attempt by an admitted drug
dealer to make a name for himself in a notorious prison-based gang.
   Tyrone Robinson, 25, told investigators Friday he fatally shot
Newton in self-defense after the one-time activist brandished a gun
in a desperate act to obtain crack, Police Sgt. Dan Mercado said.
   Other witnesses told police Newton was unarmed, Mercado said.
   Robinson, on parole for robbery, was arrested Tuesday on a
weapons charge 14 hours after Newton's death and about a block from
the scene of the killing. He admitted to the killing Friday morning,
while still in custody, was charged with investigation of murder and
faces arraignment Tuesday, Mercado said.
   ``He wanted to be a high mucky-muck; he was a foot soldier and he
wanted to be a shot-caller,'' Mercado said.
   Robinson ``considered the murder a means to advance'' in the gang
hierarchy of the Black Guerrilla Family, Mercado said.
   At a news conference Friday, police said they believed the
confrontation was the latest in a series of run-ins between Newton
and the drug-dealing gang.
   It occurred in a neighborhood where Newton, as minister of
defense for the Black Panther Party, helped set up social programs
to combat racism and help destitute blacks in the 1960s.
   Newton, 47, more recently had a history of substance abuse and
entered a hospital treatment program in 1984. Police said they
believe he had been using cocaine throughout Monday evening and
early Tuesday.
   Mercado said Newton crossed the Black Guerrilla Family several
times by stealing drugs, including earlier this summer when Robinson
said he was robbed by Newton of 14 crack pieces worth $160. Highly
potent and addictive, crack consists of the hard, pebblelike pieces
of cocaine prepared for smoking. Newton and Robinson had known each
other for about two years, said police.
   The Black Guerrilla Family operates on the streets of West Coast
cities and in California's maximum-security prisons, including San
Quentin Prison, where Newton served time earlier this year for a
parole violation.
   According to a police account, Newton went to a ``crack house''
in a drug-torn west Oakland neighborhood early Tuesday and caused a
commotion in an attempt to obtain the drug.
   He was told to leave the house and ran into Robinson a short
distance away.
   Robinson said Newton pulled a gun and demanded drugs. Robinson
said he refused to sell the drugs to Newton and shot him in
self-defense.
   Mercado said a man accompanying Robinson witnessed the shooting,
but police did not divulge whether the man, arrested Friday for
investigation of auto theft, backed up Robinson's claim of
self-defense. Police did not release the man's identity.
   Police said they recovered the 9mm handgun they believe was used
in Newton's slaying, but provided no other details. Ballistic test
results are pending.
   Two other men were arrested with Robinson on Tuesday, also on
weapons charges, but are not considered suspects in the Newton
killing, Mercado said.
   Earlier Friday, a radical group held an angry protest that blamed
the government for Newton's death. Newton's funeral is Monday.
   At least 40 members and supporters of Uhuru House took part in a
noontime march in Oakland during which they chanted, ``Who killed
Huey? Don't you tell no lie, it was the government, the government,
the FBI.''
   Congressional hearings in 1976 revealed that FBI infiltrators
sought to disrupt the Black Panthers and their efforts contributed
to the downfall of the organization.
</TEXT>
