<FIRST>r i PM-China-Cars     08-26 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Cars,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Confiscates 2,700 Cars From Freewheeling Bureaucrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's Shanxi province has confiscated 2,700 cars
from bureaucrats who squandered public money, according to an
official report today.
   The Guangming Daily said the northern province, one of China's
poorest, earned $13.5 million by reselling the vehicles and fining
government departments that illegally purchased the cars last year.
   The money will go to education, boosting the province's education
budget by 7.1 percent this year, the newspaper said.
   New cars have been a main target of a yearlong government
campaign to cut waste and reduce public spending. The Communist
Party Politburo last month barred all senior party and government
leaders from driving imported cars.
   But the Guangming Daily said local departments in Shanxi had
ignored government restrictions on buying new vehicles, and that
many cars were obtained fraudulently.
   Some offices used money set aside for natural disasters and
education, while others used their cars for personal pleasure and
profit, the daily reported. Many of the offices registered their
cars in the names of individuals or army units.
   Offices found violating regulations on buying cars were fined 30
percent to 40 percent of the car's value, the daily said.
</TEXT>
