<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Japan     08-26 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Japan,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Seek Japan's Business With Declassified Military Technology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is courting more Japanese business
by dangling the possibility of access to declassified military
technology, including the know-how that went into building the
Soviet space shuttle, Tass said.
   On Friday, Soviet and Japanese business officials ended a
three-day meeting in Moscow. The chiefs of the Japanese delegation
were also received in the Kremlin by Prime Minister Nikolai I.
Ryzhkov.
   The Soviets hope Japan will serve as a source of capital and
technology they can use for modernizing their country's stagnant
economy, especially in the vast, underdeveloped stretches of eastern
Siberia.
   Vladislav Malkevich, chairman of the Soviet Chamber of Commerce,
said his delegation made a pitch for more trade by offering access
to defense technology that has been declassified in keeping with the
reforms of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``What is at issue is certainly not joint SS-20 missile
production,'' Malkevich told a Friday news conference. ``But many of
the recently declassified defense technologies could be of interest
to Japanese firms.
   ``A packet of proposals for such cooperation, including part of
the technologies of the Soviet Buran reusable spaceship, was handed
over to them in the course of the meeting.''
   At the Kremlin, Ryzhkov called for creating joint enterprises in
the Soviet Far East and Siberia to process timber and foodstuffs and
manufacture consumer goods, Tass said.
   The Soviet prime minister told his guests the Kremlin is seeking
``full-blooded and good-neighborly relations'' with Japan.
</TEXT>
