<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rumble over Central Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developing along a cold front doused parts of
Nebraska and northeastern Colorado early today, while showers were
scattered throughout the South.
   Thunderstorms also brought high winds and rain over eastern
Kansas, where winds gusted to 70 mph near Melvern Friday evening and
3 inches of rain drenched Emporia.
   Late evening thunderstorms in western Nebraska produced golf
ball-size hail at Chappell.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued over eastern North Dakota and
over the southern Plains early today. Evening thunderstorms in
eastern New Mexico deluged Lea County with more than 2 inches of
rain.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms developing along a
stationary front were scattered over Iowa, Georgia and South
Carolina early today. A few showers and thunderstorms also rumbled
over Alabama and northern Florida.
   Heavier rainfall for the six hour period ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included 1} inches at Des Moines, Iowa.
   Temperatures fell to the 40s and 50s in the Northeast, the Great
Lakes region and the Northwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at McCall, Idaho, to 86 degrees at Phoenix.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms over much
of the upper Mississippi Valley, Wisconsin, northern Illinois,
Indiana, southwest Ohio, Kentucky and eastern Tennessee; scattered
showers and thunderstorms over the Georgia coast and the Florida
peninsula; and possible severe thunderstorms over eastern Nebraska
and Iowa.
