<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Jet     08-26 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Britain-Jet,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight Diverted to Montreal After False Fire Alert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Airways jumbo jet with 291 passengers
flying from Chicago to London's Heathrow Airport diverted in
mid-flight to Montreal following a false-alarm fire alert, the
airline reported.
   An airline spokesman said Flight BA298, a Boeing 747, had taken
off Friday night from Chicago bound for Heathrow when a warning
light on the flight deck indicated a fire in the cargo hold.
   ``The captain decided to divert to the nearest available airport,
which happened to be Montreal, as a natural precaution,'' said the
spokesman, who in accordance with British practice spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``It turned out there was no fire and the warning light had come
on because of an electrical fault,'' he said.
   He said the passengers were booked into a Montreal hotel for the
night before resuming their journey in the same plane today.
</TEXT>
