<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0632EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RacialAttack     08-26 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Attack,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Charge Five But Still Seek Shooter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched for an 18-year-old suspect and
put bulletproof vests on five young white men subjected to death
threats after they were charged with participating in a fatal racial
attack.
   The five were charged Friday in the death of Yusef Hawkins, 16,
who was shot Wednesday night when he and three friends, all black,
went to the mostly white Bensonhurst neighborhood of Brooklyn to try
to buy a used car.
   Police said Hawkins and his friend ran into a gang of 10 to 30
young people armed with baseball bats and at least one gun in rage
against interracial dating.
   Parallels to the 1986 Howard Beach case deepened as it emerged
that one of Hawkins' companions, Luther Sylvester, 17, is a cousin
of Michael Griffith. Griffith was chased to his death in Howard
Beach by a gang of white teen-agers angry that blacks entered their
neighborhood.
   As condemnation mounted from civil rights leaders and candidates
in this year's city elections, police announced a $10,000 reward for
information leading to other arrests and convictions in the case.
   The New York Times and the Daily News reported in their Saturday
editions that witnesses identified an 18-year-old as the gunman and
that he was the subject of an intensive manhunt. Officially, police
said only that a sixth youth was wanted for questioning.
   The suspects charged Friday were led out of a police station
wearing bulletproof vests.
   An anonymous caller had told a desk sergeant that ``they were
going to get those guys as soon as they left the station,''
Inspector Richard Mayronne said.
   Police said the racial tragedy resulted from the anger of a young
man who was jilted by a girlfriend who began dating a dark-skinned
Hispanic man. The gang gathered to waylay black or Hispanics youths
they thought were coming to the neighborhood to attend Gina
Feliciano's 18th birthday party.
   Miss Feliciano, fearing trouble, had called off the party, and
the white youths attacked Hawkins and his friends, Sylvester,
Stanford, 18, and Troy Banner, 18.
   Keith Mondello, 18, who police say was Miss Feliciano's former
boyfriend, Steven Curreri, 18, Pasquale Raucci, 19, and Charles
Stressler, 21, were charged with assault, riot, aggravated
harassment, violation of civil rights, and menacing and possessing a
weapon, a baseball bat. Mondello and Curreri also were charged with
conspiracy.
   James Patino, 24, was charged with assault, riot, aggravated
harassment and violation of civil rights.
   Police who impounded Modello's car and opened it after waiting
for a search warrant said they found a bat inside, but no gun.
   Figures who played key roles in the Howard Beach drama also
entered the Bensonhurst case within hours of the shooting.
   Stephen Murphy, the lawyer who won the only acquittal among the
major Howard Beach defendants, is representing one of the white
Brooklyn youths. C. Vernon Mason, who as attorney for one of the
Howard Beach survivors forced appointment of a special prosecutor,
is representing Stanford.
   Murphy said Mondello was not the boyfriend jilted by Miss
Feliciano. He said Mondello conceded being at the scene and having a
bat, but maintained the youth was armed to protect himself against
the girl's threat that her black and Hispanic friends would beat him
up.
   Police said Miss Feliciano was cooperating with the investigation.
   David Dinkins, the only black candidate in the Sept. 12 mayoral
primary, condemned the racism underlying the attack by saying: ``It
wasn't mistaken identity. It was a case of any nigger will do.''
   The New York Urban League renewed its call for appointment of a
permanent special prosecutor for bias crimes. The league president,
Donald Polk, also proposed setting up sting operations in
neighborhoods with histories or recent incidents of racially
motivated harassment or violence.
   ``We in New York are, once again, confronted with an unacceptable
racial disaster ... another intolerable incident of racial
violence,'' said Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York
Civil Liberties Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
