<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0646EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StarvationTrial     08-26 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Starvation Trial,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Begins For Parents in Starvation Death of Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) _ The parents of a 14-year-old boy never
meant for their oldest child to die, believing throughout a 42-day
fast that the Lord would save them from a financial crisis, their
attorney said.
   Larry and Leona Cottam, accused of murder in the starving death
of their son, Eric, had hoped their faith would sustain them through
hard times, defense attorney Al Flora said during opening statements
Friday in the Cottams' trial in Luzerne County court.
   Flora said the couple and their 12-year-old daughter, Laura, were
shocked when they found Eric dead Jan. 3 at their home in nearby
Nuangola.
   ``They never believed anyone would die and they thought God would
intervene,'' Flora said.
   Mrs. Cottam wept quietly throughout the opening arguments, while
her husband, a former minister in the Seventh-day Adventist Church,
sat stoically beside her.
   After Eric's death, his parents and sister were hospitalized for
malnutrition. The family went without food for six weeks despite
having saved $3,775 they said was a tithe belonging to God, police
said.
   The 5-foot-9-inch teen-ager weighed 69 pounds when he died.
   In other statements, Flora said the Cottams did not seek help
because authorities did nothing years earlier when the couple
learned their children had been sexually molested. He said they were
too scared to turn to outsiders because they were afraid the
children would be taken from them and hurt.
   ``The evidence will show more than anything else they feared the
very thing we look to for help,'' Flora said.
   Assistant District Attorney Ann Cianflone told the jury, brought
from Philadelphia because of pre-trial publicity, that the family
wanted to eat. She said Eric had tried to stay alive by eating roots
from the back yard and hiding a frying pan and oil in his bedroom.
   ``All the evidence will show that for a six-week period of time,
Larry and Leona Cottam did nothing to get out of the situation they
were in,'' she said.
   ``They did not call for help. They did not call for assistance
until after Eric Cottam had died.''
   Flora suggested during his opening arguments that the Cottam
children had been sexually molested sometime during late 1983 or
early 1984 when they attended a one-room, church-affiliated school.
   The Cottams had enrolled their children in the school, which had
only five other students at the time, when they moved to Luzerne
County after Larry Cottam had been assigned to be the pastor of four
area churches.
   Flora said the couple became concerned after Laura began
screaming in the middle of the night and would awaken, crying and
trembling. The couple pulled their children from the school.
   It was only after the couple moved to Pittsburgh, where Larry
Cottam became pastor of another church, that they learned of the
reasons behind Laura's nightmares, Flora said.
   Flora said the Cottams sought medical treatment for the children
and at the urging of hospital officials contacted state and Luzerne
County law enforcement officials for help.
   When authorities didn't take action for several months, the
Cottams decided to retreat from the outside world, Flora said.
   They moved back to Luzerne County, teaching their children at
home, and turning to God for help from financial problems when
Cottam lost his job as a truck driver, Flora said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890826-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru   08-26 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0442,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captured Documents, U.S. Arms Back Crackdown; Traffickers Threaten
Judges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout with 21 grafs to UPDATE with drug lord's son interrogated,
Barco speech, ADDS details on documents; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of troops guarded a drug
kingpin's estate northwest of the capital where police seized a
bunker in a shootout and found documents containing the names of
lawyers and others working for dealers, reporters and officials said.
   The son of a leading drug lord was arrested in the raid and
questioned on Friday, police said.
   Meanwhile, cocaine traffickers threatened to kill 10 judges for
every drug suspect extradited to the United States in Colombia's war
on drugs, and hundreds of judges said they would quit if they don't
receive more protection.
   Washington said it was sending $65 million in helicopters,
weapons and other equipment to help the nation's week-old anti-drug
offensive. Bolivia and Ecuador also received two more U.S.
helicopters for the drug war, officials said.
   Police said arsonists hired by traffickers set fire to a country
club outside Medellin, home of the world's largest cocaine cartel,
continuing attacks on establishment targets that began with bombings
and arson Thursday. Police said the fire damaged two rooms.
   Authorities have arrested thousands of suspects and seized
hundreds of millions of dollars in property since the crackdown
began following the assassination of presidential hopeful Luis
Carlos Galan Aug. 18. President Virgilio Barco Thursday said no
property would be returned unless the owners appeared in person to
claim it.
   Thousands of students wearing black armbands paraded Friday
through downtown Bogota to Galan's tomb at the Metropolitan Cemetery.
   Barco, in a nationwide address on television and radio Friday
night, declared he was ``willing to go as far as is necessary'' to
wipe out the illegal drug empire.
   A day after traffickers declared ``total and absolute war,''
Barco told them ``the Colombian people have taken up the challenge.
They must know we will not retreat before any danger.''
   Army officials announced the discovery of financial documents in
a fortified rural bunker belonging to Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha,
reputed to be the second-ranking leader and financial brain of the
Medellin cartel. They said his son, Freddy Rodriguez Gacha, was
among those arrested in the raid Thursday near the town of Pacho, 60
miles northwest of Bogota.
   The estate was seized by the military, which exchanged gunshots
with Rodriguez Gacha's son, two nephews and seven bodyguards, the
officers told reporters of the Bogota daily El Tiempo.
   The reporters said at least 500 soldiers had cordoned off the
area Friday and were backed by six armored cars.
   Army intelligence officers interrogated the younger Rodriguez and
the bodyguards of his father, considered second in the Medellin
Cartel after Pablo Escobar Gaviria.
   Officials said the documents proved countless of the Medellin
drug cartel's criminal operations. Reporters who visited the
fortress Friday said the evidence included bookkeeping accounts and
would support incrimination of a number of real estate companies,
lawyers and other individuals in Bogota and other Colombian cities.
   Also arrested recently was Luis Fernando Galeano Berrios,
allegedly Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha's chief accountant.
   A U.S. Air Force C-5 transport plane brought in two Bell 212
helicopters that were delivered to Colombian authorities. The White
House said $20 million in aid would arrive next week.
   Anti-narcotics police of Bolivia and Ecuador received two
helicopters each during the previous 24 hours, said diplomatic and
government sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity. They said
it underscored U.S. determination to help Latin America fight drug
traffickers.
   Bolivia and Ecuador are two main sources of the cocaine processed
in Colombia.
   About 550 judges in Bogota and the surrounding province of
Cundinamarca announced plans Friday to resign to protest what they
feel is insufficient security measures. In Cali, judges staged a
two-hour strike.
   Judge Omar Eduardo Garces Bueno of Cali told reporters he and
others received threatening letters from the ``Extraditables'' _ the
name used by traffickers in their communiques.
   In the letters, the drug dealers vowed to kill 10 judges for each
suspected trafficker extradited.
   As part of the anti-narcotics war, Barco reinstated an
extradition agreement with the United States, where numerous drug
dealers are wanted.
   Since 1981, 220 judges, magistrates and judicial employees have
been killed in a campaign of terror aimed at intimidating the courts
into dropping prosecution of drug cases.
   Since Aug. 16, when Bogota magistrate Carlos Valencia Garcia was
gunned down, judges nationwide have demanded better security. They
staged a strike that ended Wednesday, although 48 Bogota judges
refused to withdraw their letters of resignation. The Supreme Court
rejected the 48 resignations on Thursday.
   The country's 32-year-old justice minister, Monica de Grieff,
said in a television interview Friday that she ``wasn't prepared to
work in times of war, such as now.''
   Bogota was rife with rumors that Mrs. de Grieff was considering
resigning, but her office refused comment. She is known to be a
target of traffickers' death threats.
</TEXT>
