<FIRST>r a PM-Knight-RidderAppointment     08-26 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Knight-Ridder Appointment,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Batten to Succeed Chapman as Knight-Ridder Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc.'s chief executive officer, James
K. Batten, will become chairman of the media company's board
effective Oct. 1, replacing outgoing chairman Alvah Chapman.
   Batten, 53, who also serves as a board member of The Associated
Press, will retain his post as Knight-Ridder CEO when he assumes the
chairmanship, the company said Friday.
   Chapman, 68, has headed the board since 1982. He is to continue
to serve as chairman of the company's executive committee and as a
member of the board.
   He also will also serve as a consultant to Knight-Ridder.
   ``Everyone who cares about Knight-Ridder and has a stake in its
success will be forever indebted to Alvah Chapman,'' Batten said.
   ``In the Chapman years, Knight-Ridder has grown steadily stronger
in its performance on behalf of all our stakeholders _ our
customers, our employees, our communities and our shareholders,'' he
said.
   ``I have honored my commitment,'' Chapman said, ``to the board
and CEO Jim Batten when I delayed my retirement at their request
almost 18 months beyond our mandatory retirement age.''
   Batten is a Suffolk, Va., native who began his career as editor
of the newspaper at Davidson College in North Carolina. He went on
to work as a reporter for The Charlotte Observer and Knight-Ridder's
Washington bureau, then served in editorial positions at the Detroit
Free Press and the Observer before becoming Knight-Ridder's vice
president for news in 1975.
   P. Anthony Ridder, 48, will continue as president of
Knight-Ridder's newspaper division.
   Last month, the company announced that Richard G. Capen Jr.,
publisher of The Miami Herald, will become vice chairman of
Knight-Ridder effective Sept. 1, and David Lawrence Jr., publisher
at the Free Press, will become Herald publisher.
   Chapman was Knight-Ridder's CEO from 1976 until 1988, when Batten
took the job. Chapman graduated from The Citadel in 1942 with a
bachelor of science degree in business administration, and was a
bomber pilot in World War II.
   After the war, he joined the Columbus (Ga.) Ledger-Enquirer, and
became executive vice president and general manager of the St.
Petersburg Times in 1953.
   In 1957, he became part owner, president and publisher of the
Savannah (Ga.) Morning News and Evening Press. He joined the Knight
organization three years later, and moved up to vice president and
general manager of the Herald, before becoming president in 1969.
   Chapman was named president of Knight Newspapers in 1973, and
became the first president of Knight-Ridder Newspapers Inc. at the
time of the merger in 1974.
   Knight-Ridder owns 29 daily newspapers, and is completing the
sale of its eight broadcast stations. Other company investments
include cable television and business information services.
</TEXT>
