<HEAD>Korean War Vet Elected VFW Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decorated Army infantry squad leader who
served in the Korean War has been elected commander-in-chief of the
Veterans of Foreign Wars.
   Walter Hogan, of Greenfield, Wis., replaces Vietnam War veteran
Larry W. Rivers as head of the 2.1 million-member veterans'
organization.
   Hogan, in an acceptance speech Friday at the VFW's national
convention, promised to continue efforts to obtain better medical
care for America's 27 million veterans. He acknowledged that the
federal government is spending more money than ever, about $30
billion this budget year, but said it is ``buying less and less
health care.''
   The VFW also will push for a constitutional amendment banning the
burning of the American flag, he told delegates.
