<DOCNO> AP890826-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0716EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Gay-Bashing     08-26 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gay-Bashing,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder Convictions in Gay Attack Reversed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court overturned the murder
convictions of three men in an alleged ``gay-bashing,'' ruling that
the evidence failed to justify the convictions.
   The 1st District Court of Appeal said Friday that no murderous
blows were struck before the victim's head fatally struck the
pavement. The court said the man was struck twice _ slapped and
probably punched.
   ``The attack was unprovoked and seems clearly to have been
motivated solely by (the three men's) mindless homophobia,'' said
Justice William Newsom in the appeals court's 2-1 ruling.
   The court cited the legal standard for murder when no intent to
kill is shown: acting deliberately, and in disregard for human life,
a person must commit an act that is inherently life-threatening.
   That standard cannot be met by a beating unless it is ``so brutal
that death is a probable consequence,'' said Newsom.
   The court ordered the convictions reduced to involuntary
manslaughter _ a death resulting from an ordinary assault _ with a
maximum sentence of four years.
   If upheld, the ruling would reduce the men's convictions from
second-degree murder to involuntary manslaughter. Lawyers for two of
the men said they would be eligible for immediate release from
prison, where they have been since 1984 on sentences of 15 years to
life.
   ``Any anti-gay behavior is despicable, and people should be
prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law,'' said Maureen Kallins,
lawyer for defendant Timothy White. ``But this was never a murder.
... Tim White slapped someone and a slap does not make him a
murderer.''
   Deputy Attorney General Blair Hoffman said there was a good
chance the state would appeal the ruling. He said it was ``a close
question'' whether the men's actions were life-threatening, a
requirement for a murder conviction, but that the appeals court
should have let the jury resolve the issue.
   White, then 22, and co-defendants Donny Clanton, 19, and David
Rogers, 19, had driven 40 miles to San Francisco from their homes in
Vallejo. A witness quoted Rogers as saying, ``Let's go beat up some
faggots.''
   The men went to an area of San Francisco frequented by
homosexuals and pursued two passers-by. One, John O'Connell, 41, was
struck and knocked to the sidewalk; he went into a coma and died
days later. The court said the cause of death was the impact of his
head on the pavement.
   The killing, and several other assaults to which the men pleaded
guilty, prompted a public outcry. Then Mayor Dianne Feinstein posted
a $10,000 reward in the case, and a state law was passed increasing
damages in suits by victims of ``gay-bashing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890826-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0717EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola     08-26 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zairean President, South African Leader Pledge Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOMA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mobutu Sese Seko and South African
leader F.W. de Klerk pledged cooperation but reported no
breakthroughs in talks aimed at rescuing a faltering peace agreement
in Angola.
   De Klerk, on his first diplomatic mission since he became acting
president Aug. 15, conferred for nearly three hours Friday with
Mobutu at his resort home on the shores of Lake Kivu in northeastern
Zaire.
   A joint communique described the talks as ``positive, opportune
and constructive, particularly at this critical state of
developments in Angola.''
   The statement said the leaders agreed on the need for more
discussions. They refused to answer any questions at a lakeside
luncheon following the talks.
   The Angolan government and the rebels agreed June 22 to a
cease-fire brokered by Mobutu, but the opposing sides have
repeatedly accused each other of violations. Rebel leader Jonas
Savimbi said Thursday that the truce was over, and told his forces
to prepare for further fighting.
   An official close to Friday's discussions, who requested
anonymity, suggested South Africa and Zaire would try to keep the
peace process alive by serving as intermediaries between Angola's
Marxist government and the U.S.-backed guerrilla movement.
   Mobutu has been leading efforts to negotiate a settlement of
Angola's civil war, and South Africa endorsed his initiative after
halting military assistance to the guerrillas last year.
   De Klerk is to meet Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda in
Livingstone, Zambia, on Monday _ a scheduled trip that led to his
appointment as acting president after P.W. Botha resigned in anger
over the plans.
   As leader of South Africa's ruling National Party, de Klerk is
favored to win election to a five-year term as president after
parliamentary elections Sept. 6.
   The guerrilla group, the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, has been fighting since 1975 for a
power-sharing agreement with the Angolan government.
   The United States supplies the rebels with about $15 million in
aid annually and routes supplies through Zaire.
   The Angolan government and the rebels said Friday that more than
200 people had died in fighting this past week in central and
southern Angola. The casualty toll was one of the highest reported
since a cease-fire was declared in Angola in June.
   The rebels, in a statement released in Lisbon, claimed they
killed 77 government soldiers who attacked rebel positions earlier
this week.
   In Washington Friday, the Bush administration urged warring
Angolan factions to reach a cease-fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
