<DOCNO> AP890826-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0849EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Poland     08-26 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Poland,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda: Don't Count Poland's Communists Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish Communists may have suffered a defeat, but
nobody should write their political obituary, the Soviet Communist
Party daily Pravda said today in what appeared to be a warning to
Polish radicals.
   With the election of Soldarity member Tadeusz Mazowiecki as
Polish prime minister, Pravda said ``extremist-minded people are
hurrying to write off the Polish United Workers Party because, they
argue, it has finally found itself in isolation, abandoned by its
associates.''
   That would be premature, Pravda cautioned. In fact, it said, the
Communists by right are the most important group in Polish politics.
``One should not ignore the fact that the PUWP _ a more than
2-million-strong party of Communists _ remains the leading force of
society and has always worked and acted for the good of the people,
repeatedly led the country out of deep crises and been a herald of
all progressive reforms,'' the Soviet paper said.
   Mazowiecki's election on Thursday, with the support of many
Communist lawmakers, gave the Soviet Union and their East bloc
allies the first non-Communist chief of government in the region
since World War II.
   Mazowiecki was chosen after parliamentary elections in which
Communist candidates were trounced and after a Communist prime
minister was unable to form a government in the face of opposition
from the Solidarity labor movement.
   The Soviet government sent an immediate telegram of
congratulations to Mazowiecki, but Pravda's commentary, the most
authoritative to date, cast doubt on whether Mazowiecki can succeed
in breaking Poland's economic decline.
   ``Is this the way out of the labyrinth?'' the newspaper asked in
a headline. It never really answered the question.
   The Kremlin has repeatedly said Polish politics are purely a
matter for Poles to decide. But Pravda gave a picture of events in
the Soviet Union's western neighbor that must have seemed quite
familiar to Soviets who have seen promises of political reform at
home accompanied by food shortages and unrest.
   And yet the Polish Communist Party ``has not been discouraged,
has not given up its lofty and necessary mission to renew socialism,
to achieve national concord and to reform the economy,'' Pravda said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
