<FIRST>r i PM-GermanRefugees     08-26 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-German Refugees,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>100 More East Germans Cross Into Austria</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Austria-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EISENSTADT, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 East Germans fleeing
their communist homeland defied increased Hungarian border controls
and crossed illegally into Austria, authorities said today.
   The Austria Press Agency quoted unidentified law enforcement
officials in Eisenstadt near the border as saying the East Germans
crossed into Austria overnight individually or in small family
groups.
   That marked a change from recent mass escape attempts.
   Hungary announced Friday that it would increase its contingent of
border guards because they have been overwhelmed by up to 500
escapees at a time.
   The flight of politically and economically disenchanted East
Germans into Austria began after Hungary tore down most of the
barriers on its side of the border in May. The move was welcomed in
the West as a sign of liberalization in Hungary, one of the Soviet
bloc's most reform-minded countries.
   But it has led to tensions with East Germany, which has declined
to follow the East bloc reform movement, which began in the Soviet
Union.
   West German officials estimate that since July 5,000 East Germans
with little chance of legal travel to the West have used Hungary _ a
Warsaw Pact ally that they can visit freely _ as an illegal transit
point to the West.
   West Germany, which welcomes all East Germans immigrants, has
exerted pressure on Hungary as well, calling for a humane solution
to the problem.
   Hundreds of East Germans also are refusing to leave West German
diplomatic property in Budapest, Hungary; Prague, Czechoslovakia;
and East Berlin, unless they are guaranteed safe passage to West
Germany.
</TEXT>
