<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0466 08-26 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Clashes Diminish During Soviet Cease-fire Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 3rd pvs, `He said...,' to UPDATE with
Cyprus halting helicopter flights. Pickup 4th pvs, `By police...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners battled with
howitzers today, but a police spokesman said the clashes had
slackened since a Soviet envoy started a bid to secure a stable
cease-fire.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules, said
four hours of predawn shelling subsided after 7 a.m. into
intermittent exchanges of machine gunfire and 60mm mortar rounds
across the city's dividing Green Line.
   He said two people were killed and nine wounded in the artillery
duel, which also targeted Christian ports north of the city and
Syrian gun emplacements in Moslem west Beirut.
   The Cyprus government today halted daily flights by military
helicopter between Cyprus and Lebanon's besieged Christian enclave,
sources reported.
   A Lebanese embassy source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the ban and called it ``a temporary measure.''
   The Cyprus government declined comment, but one source said the
ban was imposed because Lebanon violated an agreement to use the
flights for humanitarian purposes only and was using them to carry
Christian military personnel.
   The helicopter flights and a daily hydrofoil service between the
Christian port of Jounieh and the Cypriot port of Larnaca, next to
the airport, have been the Christian enclave's only links with the
outside world.
   By police count, 796 people have been killed and 2,231 wounded
since the fighting began March 8 between Christian army commander
Gen. Michel Aoun's troops and Syrian forces backed by Moslem militia
allies.
   The spokesman said ``the intensity of the Syrian-Christian
clashes has diminished noticeably'' since Soviet envoy Gennady
Tarasov arrived Wednesday on a mission to halt the latest round of
violence in Lebanon's 14-year-civil war.
   Tarasov, who heads the Soviet Foreign Ministry's Middle East
department, talked with Aoun and Moslem Lebanese leaders before
leaving Friday for Damascus for meetings with Syrian officials.
   Syria, a close Soviet ally, claims to be in full agreement with
Moscow over Lebanon, which it considers within its sphere of
influence. But Tarasov's talks with Aoun contradicted the Syrian
refusal to accept the Maronite Catholic general as a negotiating
partner.
   Aoun has declared a ``war of liberation'' against Syria. He says
Syria's 40,000 troops, in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate, have betrayed their mission by fighting on the
Moslem side.
   Tarasov said after meeting Aoun on Friday the Soviet Union
``strongly believes there are no military solutions to the Lebanese
problems.''
   A source close to Aoun, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the general told Tarasov of his ``full readiness to cooperate with
the Soviet effort'' on Lebanon.
   He said the Soviet envoy was working on ``a formula accepted to
all for stabilizing the security situation and lifting the
blockade'' imposed by Syria on the 310-square-mile Christian enclave
north of Beirut.
   Syria and its allies laid siege to the enclave in retaliation for
Aoun's March 6 blockade of illegal militia-run ports south of Beirut
aimed at retrieving lost taxes estimated at $100 million annually.
   A senior Moslem official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said Tarasov ``offered Soviet guarantees covering the security part
of a plan to defuse the situation and address the political crisis.''
   Lebanon's Moslems, who make up a majority of the country's
population, are seeking political reform guaranteeing an equal share
of power with the traditionally dominant Christians.
   The Moslem official said the Soviet mission focused on reviving a
three-member Arab League mediation committee's peace effort in
Lebanon.
   The committee, comprising leaders of Morocco, Saudi Arabia and
Algeria, said July 28 it had reached an impasse because Syria
refused to agree to setting a timetable for pulling its troops out
of Lebanon.
   Syrian-Christian clashes escalated sharply after the committee's
report, which Aoun considered a victory for his cause.
   The Moslem source said the Soviet diplomatic effort ``did not
contradict'' the deployment of a flotilla of French warships in the
eastern Mediterranean off the Lebanese coast.
   ``The Soviet effort is the carrot and the French naval buildup is
the stick,'' the source said.
   He added that the French naval presence ``is a message'' to the
Syrians and their allies that ``storming through the (Christian)
enclave is not permitted.''
   ``It is the same message that Tarasov delivered at the diplomatic
level,'' he saidl.
   There have been reports the Syrians and Moslems militias were
planning to launch massive ground attacks against the enclave, home
to about 1 million Christians.
</TEXT>
