<FIRST>r i PM-Vatican-Poland 1stLd-Writethru   08-26 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0476,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Bloc Gets its First Ambassador to Vatican</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: Adds 3 grafs to UPDATE with new diplomat for Algeria, Tunisia.
No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today appointed a Polish
Vatican official as the first papal nuncio or ambassador to Poland
since that country's Communist government severed ties to the Holy
See in 1945.
   Monsignor Jozef Kowalczyk, who was born in Tarnow, Poland, has
been the head of the Polish section of the Vatican secretariat of
state since 1978.
   Also today, the Polish state news service PAP announced the
appointment of Jerzy Kuberski, 59, as ambassador to the Holy See.
Kuberski has been in charge of Poland's working contacts with the
Holy See since 1982.
   Kowalczyk, who turns 51 on Monday, will be the only full nuncio
to a Warsaw Pact country. Cuba and Yugoslavia are the only other
Communist countries with full diplomatic relations with the Vatican.
   The Vatican and Poland restored full diplomatic ties on July 17,
two months after Poland's Parliament granted legal recognition to
the Roman Catholic Church. That recognition came after 15 years of
permanent working contacts between the Vatican and the Communist
government.
   It is the first restoration of relations between the Vatican and
a Warsaw Pact country that tried to muzzle organized religion after
World War II.
   Kowalcyzk's appointment was unusual in that he is from the
country where he will serve as nuncio. Ordained a priest in 1962,
Kowalcyzk worked for the Synod of Bishops and in the Vatican
department for the sacraments before he joined the secretariat of
state. He also heads a commission for the publication of John Paul's
writings from the years before he became the first Polish pope.
   Kuberski, a Communist Party member, has been charge d'affaires at
the Polish Embassy to the Vatican since Poland and the Holy See
re-established formal relations.
   His appointment was made by President Wojciech Jaruzelski. Under
Poland's revamped constitution, the president controls ambassadorial
appointments.
   Kuberski is a former member of the Communist Party Central
Committee and a former director of the Office of Religious Affairs.
   As head of the Team for Permanent Working Contacts with the Holy
See, he has lived the past seven years in Rome.
   Also today, the pope named Monsignor Edmond Farhat to be the
apostolic pro-nuncio in Algeria and Tunisia and the apostolic
delegate in Libya.
   As the pro-nuncio, Farhat, 56, will be the chief Vatican diplomat
in Algeria and Tunisia. He will also be the chief Vatican diplomat
in Libya, but the title apostolic delegate indicates he is
accredited to the local church instead of the government.
   Farhat was born May 20, 1933, in Ain Kfaa, Lebanon, and was
ordained March 28, 1959. He has been an undersecretary in the Synod
of Bishops since 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
