<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0464 08-26 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>30 Arrested During Protest of Rugby Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with more arrests. Pickup 6th graf
pvs, `The country's...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today arrested 30
demonstrators protesting a controversial rugby tour by a squad of
international stars.
   Two separate demonstrations, held hours before the start of a
match in Cape Town, were part of a nationwide anti-apartheid
campaign launched Aug. 2 to protest segregation and the Sept. 6
parliamentary elections, which exclude the black majority.
   Twenty-eight demonstrators were arrested at a hotel after meeting
briefly with Willie John McBride, manager of the international squad
made up of Australian, French and British players.
   Two activists also were arrested when about 30 protesters
gathered outside the main branch of the First National Bank, which
is sponsoring the rugby tour.
   They were identified as Dawood Khan, a spokesman for the Western
Cape Traders Association, and Willie Hofmeyer, a leader of the
banned United Democratic Front, the country's largest anti-apartheid
coalition.
   Police on Friday banned all rallies in protest of the tour. The
international team's visit has been denounced by activists as a
breach of a sports boycott imposed to protest apartheid.
   On Friday, riot police armed with tear gas and shotguns clashed
with anti-apartheid protesters in townships near Cape Town. Police
wounded three youths and rioters reportedly killed two black men.
   The country's two largest anti-apartheid labor federations met
outside Johannesburg today and were expected to discuss possible
protest action against the Sept. 6 parliamentary elections.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   Police Commissioner Gen. Hennie de Witt on Friday imposed
restrictions on the two-day meeting of the anti-apartheid labor
groups, allowing only union members to attend, prohibiting political
banners and limiting discussions to labor issues.
   Dozens of police were present when labor officials began arriving
this morning. The two organizations are the Congress of South
African Trade Unions, which has more than 900,000 members, and the
smaller National Council of Trade Unions.
   As part of a defiance campaign led in part by the trade union
group, dozens of blacks successfully sought treatment Friday at a
whites-only hospital wing in East London and clergymen announced
plans to defy bus segregation laws in the capital city, Pretoria.
   Similar protests took place at six whites-only hospitals on Aug.
2.
   On Friday, police fired birdshot to break up a protest at
Mitchell's Plain township, wounding three mixed-race high school
students. Another police contingent set up roadblocks outside the
University of the Western Cape and fired tear gas at mixed-race and
black students who had erected barricades on the campus.
   Police officials said two officers were wounded by a gunman in
Mitchell's Plain, and reported that two black men were killed by
rioters in separate incidents elsewhere after their vehicles were
attacked, one by people hurling stones and one by a firebomb.
   In Pretoria, a group of black and white clergymen announced that
a campaign to desegregate the city's transit system will begin
Monday. The ministers said blacks would board whites-only buses and
whites would ride in mini-bus taxis, which are supposed to carry
only blacks.
   They said the weeklong campaign would be peaceful and invited
Pretoria-based foreign diplomats to observe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
