<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Church     08-26 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Church,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Rejects Church Call to Release Military Rulers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday rejected an
appeal from the Orthodox Church of Greece for release of military
rulers held in jail since their junta collapsed in 1974.
   The Holy Synod, which acts as the church's ruling body, made the
unprecedented request Friday.
   It said the former dictators should be freed ``in appreciation of
the optimistic spirit currently being cultivated for the more
general reconciliation of the Greeks and the forgetting of past
misfortunes and divisions.''
   However, government spokesman Athanassios Kanellopoulos said,
``The government was never concerned with the subject, and it does
not comment on Holy Synod announcements.''
   The current government is made up of an alliance of leftists and
conservatives.
   The military, which seized power in April 1967, was toppled in
July 1974 after it engineered an abortive coup in Cyprus. The
attempt led to a Turkish invasion of the northern part of the
Mediterranean island.
   The right-wing military dictatorship was responsible for the
widespread detention and torture of political opponents and the
suppression of a student uprising in November 1973.
   Three former junta leaders were sentenced to death in August
1975, but their sentences were later commuted to life imprisonment.
Another eight were given life terms.
</TEXT>
