<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BabySmuggling     08-26 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Baby Smuggling,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indonesians Arrested in Baby Smuggling Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Indonesians have been arrested
on suspicion of smuggling 10 babies for sale to childless couples,
state-run media said Saturday.
   The babies, found Thursday in a wooden hut in Kampung Telaga Air,
were between two and three months old, the Bernama news agency
reported. It said one of the 10 babies died during the 20-mile trip
to a hospital in Kuching, about 540 miles south of Kuala Lumpur.
   The suspects are reported to have smuggled babies from the
Indonesian part of Borneo island to the Malaysian sector on
Thursday, Bernama said.
   The arrested suspects include six women and four men between 19
and 40 years old, Bernama said. Two more women were being sought, it
said.
   The nine surviving babies were in good health and remained
hospitalized, Bernama said. Officials told the news agency they were
investigating whether the infants were kidnapped or sold by their
parents.
   Some childless Malaysians pay up to $1,860 for a baby purchased
on the black market.
</TEXT>
