<FIRST>u i AM-Korea     08-26 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indicted Opposition Leader Vows to Lead New Anti-Government Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INCHON, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political leader indicted in a North
Korean spy case said Saturday he will try rally the country's
splintered opposition forces for a new campaign to push government
reforms.
   Kim Dae-jung of the Party for Peace and Democracy said his
indictment ``is tantamount to the government of (President) Roh
Tae-woo declaring it has given up its willingness to carry out
reforms toward democracy.''
   Kim, who heads the largest opposition party, vowed to battle the
government in the National Assembly and the courts to speed
democratic reforms and wipe out legacies of past authoritarian
regimes.
   ``There are over 900 political prisoners in jail. This is more
than were jailed at any one time under the Chun Doo-hwan regime,''
he said, referring to Roh's predecessor in remarks at a news
conference.
   Kim told a news conference that his party would introduce a
resolution in the National Assembly to fire Prosecutor General Kim
Ki-chun. He is supervising the case against Kim.
   Addressing an outdoor rally of 20,000 supporters in the western
port of Inchon later on Saturday, Kim pledged to launch ``the
strongest possible'' anti-government campaign.
   Kim and two other members of his party were indicted Friday. They
were accused of failing to report to authorities about an illegal
visit to North Korea by National Assemblyman Suh Kyung-won, then a
member of Kim's party.
   Suh has been jailed on charges of violating national security
laws, espionage and accepting $120,000 from agents of the Communist
country.
   The opposition leader, who ran unsuccessfully for president in
1971 and 1987, has denied prior knowledge of Suh's trip in August
1988. Kim has said the government is attacking him an an effort to
discredit the political opposition.
   If convicted, Kim could face up to five years in prison.
   Kim said his party will begin a nationwide petition drive in
September to press for more democracy and will organize rallies in
27 cities to denounce political repression. He said his party will
join its efforts with those of other dissident forces.
   Kim Young-sam, who heads the opposition Reunification Democratic
Party, criticized the indictment of the rival party leader.
   ``The Suh case should be thoroughly investigated, but it is
nonsense to indict the head of an opposition party simply for
failing to report it to authorities,'' he told a news conference.
   His group is the second-largest opposition party. Both Kims ran
for president in 1987 during a feud among opposition forces,
splitting the opposition vote and allowing Roh to win the presidency
without a majority.
   National security laws forbid unauthorized travel to North Korea,
which South Korea has viewed as an enemy country since the peninsula
was divided in 1945. The two Koreas fought a war in 1950-53 and
never signed a peace treaty.
   In another development, about 350 radical students and families
of political prisoners held a peaceful rally at Korea University in
Seoul to denounce the Roh government. They accused authorities of
stepping up persecution of political dissenters.
   Government officials deny holding any political prisoners.
</TEXT>
