<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 1243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-GenericDrugs Bjt   08-26 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Generic Drugs, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bribes, Fraud Tarnish Generic Drugs, But Not Much</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigations of bribery and fraud
involving generic drugs have embarrassed the industry but do not
appear to be dampening the popularity of its low-cost products with
consumers.
   Industry officials and analysts say the public is so smitten with
generic drugs _ which mimic name-brand products whose patents have
expired, but cost up to 70 percent less _ there should be no
long-term damage to sales based on the revelations so far.
   The $5-billion-a-year industry has been absorbing week after week
of damaging publicity lately about falsified test results and
gratuities paid to federal officials. More is likely in the months
ahead.
   The U.S. attorney's office in Baltimore already has obtained
guilty pleas from some industry officials and federal regulators.
The Department of Health and Human Services, the Food and Drug
Administration and Congress have ongoing investigations.
   ``The image has been tarnished, there's no question,'' said
Hemant K. Shah of Warren N.J., a private financial analyst of the
generic drug industry. ``But I really don't expect anything other
than business continuing to boom for generic drug companies.''
   Jay Molishever, spokesman for the Generic Pharmaceutical Industry
Association, a trade group of 20 generic drug makers, concedes a
``fear is beginning to take hold.''
   However, Molishever adds, ``Whatever downturn may occur because
of the concern, and there is concern, we believe will be
short-term.''
   More than 400,000 prescriptions _ nearly one-third of all
prescriptions written last year in the United States _ were filled
by generic drugs. Analysts expect that market share to keep growing,
to perhaps 37 percent by 1993.
   Their optimism is bouyed by what has not been unearthed. While
instances of falsified test results and gratuities paid to federal
regulators to speed the government's approval process have been
uncovered, there have been no indications of tainted drugs.
   ``I emphasize that we have no evidence that the safety or
effectiveness of generic drugs has been compromised,'' Health and
Human Services Secretary Louis W. Sullivan said in announcing a plan
to beef up federal oversight of the industry.
   Pharmacists report no great hesitation by consumers to purchase
generic drugs, other than the 26 that the Food and Drug
Administration has recalled so far.
   To put that figure in perspective, the generic drug industry says
that of 10,000 drugs approved for sale in the United States, 8,000
are copied and sold by generic producers, with more generic versions
available all the time as patents on the original products expire.
   ``It is a little bit early, but our people are not expecting to
see a dip in generic sales,'' said Maryellen Kari, spokesperson for
the Walgreen Co., the Deerfield, Ill., based drug store chain whose
$4.9 billion in sales last year made it the nation's largest.
``There seems to be very little customer alarm generated by the
publicity.''
   Continuing investigations promise to produce more news in coming
weeks.
   The U.S. Attorney's office in Baltimore _ which has jurisdiction
because the Food and Drug Administration is headquartered in
Rockville, Md. _ so far has obtained guilty pleas from three FDA
officials, three drug company officials and two drug companies for
various crimes involving the FDA's drug approval process.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Geoffrey Garinther says his office has
spent most of its time examining gratuities paid by companies to FDA
officials to speed approvals of generic drugs in an industry in
which the first to hit the market often gets and retains a huge
share of sales.
   Only recently, he said, have investigators begun looking into
allegations of companies substituting brand-name drugs for the
generic products they claim to be testing. Under FDA procedures,
companies send potential products to independent laboratories for
testing, and submit the results _ paperwork _ to the FDA for its
study.
   Last June, Vitarine Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Springfield Gardens,
N.Y., admitted it sought FDA approval for a generic blood pressure
drug by actually testing Dyazide, the brand-name product it was
supposed to copy.
   ``My guess is there will be guilty pleas,'' Garinther said.
   The FDA is continuing its investigations of potential
irregularities by 11 generic drug companies. The agency is also
studying the 30 most commonly used generic drugs _ accounting for 75
percent of generic drug sales _ to verify that they were approved
for sale legitimately.
   The Department of Health and Human Services is auditing the FDA,
its subdivision, to make sure its oversight of generic drugs is
effective.
   In addition, Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House
Energy and Commerce Committee, plans to continue his series of
hearings into problems within the industry and its regulation by the
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
