<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 1253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Voyager-Neptune 3rdLd-Writethru a0432 08-26 1042</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Neptune, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0432,a0481,a0490,1066</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA: Photos Show Southern Lights On Neptune, Nitrogen In Triton
Atmosphere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with evidence of broad dust bands
around planet. Picks up 6th grafs pvs, `Evidence for...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voyager 2, discovered broad, flat bands
of dust orbiting Neptune and found evidence the planet has
``southern lights,'' NASA said today.
   The probe also detected nitrogen in the atmosphere of Triton, the
moon whose pink snow and ice volcanoes were described by excited
scientists as unique in the solar system, NASA said.
   ``There's dust bands _ they're broad,'' said NASA astronomer Rich
Terrile, describing the findings from latest photorgraphs. The bands
orbit Neptune's equator, as do its narrow rings that were discovered
by Voyager earlier.
   Although Voyager has passed its closest encounters with Neptune
and Triton, it continued today to back recorded photographs taken
during the time of closest approach. And scientists and engineers
celebrated the spacecraft's successful flyby.
   ``My understanding was most of the engineers and science team had
one hell of a party last night,'' Mike Urban, a Voyager engineer,
said today.
   The one-ton space probe capped its historic 4.43-billion-mile,
12-year tour of four planets when it skimmed 3,048 miles over
Neptune's north pole Thursday night, then dove past Triton, the
planet's largest moon. It made its closest approach about 23,900
miles above the moon's surface at 2:10 a.m. PDT Friday.
   During its approach to Neptune, Voyager discovered six moons
besides Triton and Nereid, which were first observed from Earth. It
also discovered one complete ring of debris around the planet and a
partial ring, or ring arc, scientists believe will also prove to be
a complete ring.
   While only the narrow rings were visible as Voyager flew toward
Neptune, the broad dust bands became visible when they were backlit
by sunlight after the space probe passed the planet, Terrile said.
That makes them look like Saturn's broad rings, but only when viewed
from behind Neptune.
   The same thing happened when Voyager passed Uranus in 1986. That
planet had 10 narrow rings when seen by the approaching spacecraft,
which then found extensive bands of dust after passing Uranus.
Terrile said Neptune's dust bands are not as extensive.
   Evidence for the glowing lights, known as an aurora, was found at
30 degrees south latitude on Neptune as Voyager's ultraviolet light
sensor made a north-to-south scan of the planet, deputy project
scientist Ellis Miner said today.
   Because the scan didn't cover different longitudes, scientists
don't know the aurora's full extent, or whether it circles Neptune
east to west, as do Earth's auroras, Miner said.
   Miner said Voyager also found nitrogen in Triton's atmosphere.
Nitrogen makes up 78 percent of Earth's atmosphere.
   On Earth, the northern and southern lights encircle the poles,
but can get pushed closer to the equator when the sun generates
magnetic storms. However, it would be very unusual for an aurora on
Earth to get as close to the equator as 30 degrees latitude.
   Auroras are caused when electrically charged particles in the
solar wind spiral in toward a planet along magnetivc field lines. On
Earth they glow in visible light. Neptune's lights glow ultraviolet
because of hydrogen in its atmosphere.
   Engineers spent the night unloading Voyager's eight-track tape
recorder _ playing back pictures and scientific data recorded during
the Neptune and Triton rendezvous _ and also loaded new instructions
telling the probe how to point its cameras and sensors, Urban said.
   Voyager today started sending back its most detailed images of
Triton, which is four-fifth's the size of Earth's moon. But pictures
returned Friday were more than enough to stun scientists.
   ``The range of geological forms is dazzling,'' astronomer-author
Carl Sagan said Friday. ``We are almost certainly in a regime of
volcanism involving ices, maybe exotic ices'' such as water ice
mixed with frozen nitrogen or methane (natural gas).
   The photographs show a cracked, frozen Triton scarred by
thousand-foot-high ridges, fault lines, bowl-shaped craters,
mysterious domes and dark spots ringed with white halos that so far
defy explanation.
   ``The images returned this morning revealed a world unlike any
we've ever seen,'' Voyager project scientist Edward Stone said
Friday at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory.
   Icy volcanic flows have been seen on Uranus' moon Ariel and some
other moons, but Triton is the first place scientists have actually
seen ice volcanoes, Stone said. Photographs showed at least three
inactive volcanoes.
   NASA geologist Joseph Boyce said one of the ice volcanoes _ which
look like dry lakebeds filled with smooth material _ measures
several hundred miles across. Some were encircled with cliffs 1,000
to 2,000 feet high.
   The properties of exotic ices of water, methane and nitrogen
``are very different from ordinary ice,'' said Sagan, a member of
the Voyager imaging team. ``That may explain the exoticness of the
landforms.''
   Parts of the moon are frozen methane discolored by a bombardment
of radiation that produced chemical changes, Sagan said. ``We've got
pink snow. Think about how exotic that is.''
   Preliminary measurements of Triton's magnetic field suggest that
it does not have a north pole and a south pole like Earth's magnetic
field, but rather multiple poles, researchers said.
   Robert Strom of the Voyager imaging team said the relative
scarcity of craters on Triton tends to confirm speculation that
Triton originated outside the solar system and became captured by
Neptune's gravity, perhaps after colliding with one of its moons.
   Voyager also revealed that Triton has an atmosphere and is
covered with a haze of what could be photochemical smog.
   On the moon's sunlit southern hemisphere, frozen methane or other
volatile material is boiling off the surface, causing haze, and
condensing on the moon's cooler regions, scientists said.
   Voyager 2 was launched in 1977 and explored Jupiter in 1979,
Saturn in 1981 and Uranus in 1986. Until Oct. 2, Voyager 2 will look
back at Neptune. Then it will head toward interstellar space.
   Weary NASA scientists, many of whom spent all night at the
laboratory analyzing data returning from the spacecraft, gushed over
the spectacular images being received.
   Laurence Soderblom of the Voyager imaging team said: ``Wow! What
a way to leave the solar system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890826-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 1256EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     08-26 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Criticizes Communism, Lauds Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Saturday marked the 50th
anniversary of the outbreak of World War II by condemning Nazism and
Marxism as ``substitute religions'' and hailing democratic reform in
his native Poland.
   The pontiff singled out Poland while expressing support for the
right of people to determine their own governments. Poland last week
installed the first non-Communist government leader in the East Bloc.
   John Paul made his appeals in a 20-page apostolic letter marking
the Sept. 1 anniversary of the start of the war and a 12-page
message to Polish bishops on the same subject.
   In the official English translation of the letter, the pope said
in it was ``our duty before God'' to remember the war in order to
honor its victims, forgive the offenses committed, and reflect on
its causes.
   ``We have a duty to learn from the past so that never again will
there arise a set of factors capable of triggering a similar
conflagration,'' he said in the apostolic letter, according to an
official English-language text.
   He traced Nazi atrocities to its denial of God and law, which he
said led to the crushing of human rights and eventually the rights
of nations.
   ``Nazi paganism and Marxist dogma are both basically totalitarian
ideologies and tend to become substitute religions,'' he wrote in
one of his harshest condemnations yet of communism.
   Focusing on his native land, John Paul said Poland was on the
winning side of the war but that under Communist rule, Poles ``were
forced to ask themselves whether they in fact being treated as the
vanquished'' and were compelled ``to undertake new struggles.
   ``For in truth, a state whose society is not sovereign is no
sovereign state at all,'' the pope said in the message to Polish
bishops.
   John Paul was apparently referring to the campaign of the
Solidarity labor movement that culminated last week with the
appointment of a non-Communist as prime minister.
   At a news conference to release the papal documents, Cardinal
Roger Etchegaray said the pope was holding up Poland as an example.
   ``He knows very well that the Polish experience isn't limited to
a national reality but can also be applied to other situations,
above all in Europe,'' said the French cardinal, head of the
Vatican's Council for Justice and Peace.
   But asked whether the pope was advocating democracy for Eastern
Europe and the Baltic states, Etchegaray said, ``One should not
imagine that the pope tries to revise pacts, to revise Poland's
borders.''
   In his statements, the pope also made a special appeal for an end
to discrimination.
   He singled out the Nazi slaughter of the Jews as something
``which will forever remain a shame for humanity.''
   About 6 million Jews were killed in the Holocaust.
   Jews and Catholics are now embroiled in a dispute over a Catholic
convent at the site of the Auschwitz death camp in Poland.
   Jewish groups are outraged at the Polish church's refusal to move
the convent as promised. They say the convent and its Christian
symbols are insults to the memory of the 2.5 million Jews who died
there.
   Asked why the pope had not intervened, Etchegaray said: ``Knowing
the degree to which the pope respects the local churches ... the
pope shows himself even more respectful of the local church he comes
from.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
