<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 1302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-26 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 36 Killed in Sinhalese Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 20 people were shot and killed
in a central Sri Lankan village, military officals said Saturday,
and residents accused soldiers of carrying out the killings.
   Up to 16 more people were killed in various attacks during the
past 24 hours, officials said.
   All the victims of Friday's attack in Tirapanne, 100 miles
northeast of Colombo, were Sinhalese and their bodies were thrown in
six houses that were later burned, said military officials, who
cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   Residents in Anuradhapura, 12 miles from Tirapanne, blamed the
attack on soldiers in civilian clothes and said they apparently
meant to avenge the slayings of a fellow soldier's parents. The
residents, contacted by telephone, spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Pro-government vigilante groups and the military have been
accused in the past of killing civilians during operations against
Sinhalese extremists. The government denies the charge.
   An opposition lawmaker, Janak Mahendra Adikari, said in
Anuradhapura that the Tirapanne toll could be much higher. He said
hundreds of villagers had fled to Anuradhapura.
   In another attack Friday, men in military uniforms burned six or
seven homes in Katukeliyawa, 15 miles south of Anuradhapura, said
Adikari, contacted by telephone.
   ``There are reports of five to six civilian casualties in this
attack, but we do not have confirmation,'' he said. The military
could not immediately confirm the attack.
   The government armed the military with sweeping powers under
emergency laws to curb an anti-government campaign by the Sinhalese
extremists belonging to the People's Liberation Front.
   The front stepped up its campaign of assassinations and strikes
after President Ranasinghe Premadasa imposed a nationwide state of
emergency June 20. The government says at least 1,000 people have
died since July 15.
   In their latest attack, radicals detonated a bomb under a police
vehicle in Kurunegala district Friday, killing three policemen and a
civilian driver, the military officials said.
   One laborer traveling in the vehicle also was killed and five
policemen were injured in the blast about 85 miles northeast of
Colombo, the officials said.
   They said two policemen and a wildlife official were killed
Friday in an ambush of their vehicle in Anuradhapur district, which
carries the same name as its largest town.
   A naval officer, a front member and three civilians were killed
in separate incidents during the past 24 hours in southern Sri
Lanka, the officials said. One unidentified body also was found they
said.
   At least 5,000 people have died in the Sinhalese extremist
campaign, launched in July, 1987 to protest the government's peace
overtures to Tamil separatists in the northeast.
   The radicals said the government gave too many concessions to the
minority Tamil community in an India-sponsored peace plan of June
29, 1987, that aimed to end the six-year Tamil demand for an
independent nation.
   Sinhalese radicals also were angered by the deployment of Indian
peacekeeping soldiers in the northeast, invited to enforce the June,
1987, accord. They said the Indian presence compromised the
country's sovereignty.
   The accord collapsed when the strongest Tamil rebel group
rejected it, and began attacking Indian troops. At least 1,000
Indian soldiers have died in the fighting. More than 10,000 Sri
Lankans have been killed in the six-year separatist war.
   Tamils, who form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
allege discrimination in jobs and education by the Sinhalese
majority who make up 75 percent of the population.
   The Sinhalese control the government and the military.
   India became involved in the ethnic problems of its small
southeastern neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60
million Tamils.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
