<FIRST>r a PM-Lutherans 1stLd-Writethru a0431 08-26 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lutherans, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0431,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Lutheran Church Assures Recognition Of Dissent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Bishop Green...', to CORRECT first name to
Glenn, sted Green, add location of synod.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America
has decided to make sure dissenting voices are heard when the new
denomination makes a pronouncement on a controversial social issue.
   The church approved a policy of recognizing substantial minority
views Friday in a session that also affirmed membership in the
sometimes controversial National Council of Churches and World
Council of Churches. The ecumenical organizations include most major
Protestant and Eastern Orthodox churches in this country and around
the world.
   The method of handling church pronouncements, including dissent,
came in the adoption of a document detailing the basis for speaking
out on moral issues in society.
   Delegates narrowly approved an amendment offered by Christa Klein
of York, Pa., providing that whenever significant division is shown
in approving social pronouncements, summaries will be given of
dissenting positions.
   The Rev. Frank Lay of Oregon, Ill., argued this would ``reduce
the force'' of statements and the Rev. L. Edward Knudson of
Milwaukie, Ore., contended it would ``take away impact and meaning.''
   However, the Rev. Douglas Johnson of Spring Grove, Pa., said
``intelligent and moral honesty'' demanded that there be room in the
church for those who differ and that this should be openly
recognized.
   ``As a parish pastor, this is one of the problems I have
struggled with when a stand is taken with which someone doesn't
agree,'' he said.
   The provision was approved by a 489-453 vote.
   Lengthy debate preceded the vote for membership of the
5.3-million denomination, fourth-largest among U.S. Protestants, in
the National Council of Churches. The council has been involved in
leadership conflicts and financial strains and is undergoing
structural reforms.
   Bishop Glenn Nycklemoe of the Southeastern Minnesota Synod, based
in Rochester, Minn., said he had reversed his opposition to
belonging to the council, sensing ``new directions and new spirit''
in it.
   Of the three Lutheran bodies merged into the denomination, the
former Lutheran Church in America had belonged to the national
council, but not the former American Lutheran Church or former
Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches.
   The eight-day assembly, which runs through next Wednesday, also
adopted working guidelines for ecumenical efforts for Christian
unity.
   Citing the biblical and theological bases for it, the 5,000-word
document urges work for ``the oneness to which God calls the world
in the saving gift of Jesus Christ.
   ``It also means to recognize the brokenness of the church in
history and the call of God, especially in this century, to heal
this disunity of Christ's people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
