<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-USFilms     08-26 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US Films,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film Distributor Attacked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men assaulted a screenwriter who is
leading a campaign against direct distribution of U.S. films in this
country, authorities said Saturday.
   Lee Jung-ui, 45, was hospitalized for head injuries after two
unidentified men attacked him with rocks Friday in front of his
house in Seoul, police said.
   Lee blamed the attack on critics of his new job as head of an
organization opposed to direct distribution of U.S. films in South
Korea by the Hollywood-based United International Pictures, police
said.
   Lee told police he confronted two men in their 20s while
returning home from an outing with his son. He said the attackers
hit him on the head with rocks after asking, ``Aren't you Mr. Lee
Jung-ui?''
   Police were still looking for the attackers.
   On Aug. 13, six theaters in Seoul showing films distributed by
the American company, including ``Rain Man'' and ``Indiana Jones and
the Last Crusade,'' were attacked with firebombs and tear gas.
   Police said they were searching for a movie producer as a main
suspect in the theater attacks.
   Actors and other members of the South Korean film industry have
said competition from the U.S.-distributed films could wreck the
local industry.
   A trade law adopted last year allowed U.S. companies to bypass
South Korean distributors by distributing directly to cinemas.
</TEXT>
