<HEAD>Bush, Mitterrand Discuss Poland, Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lede; SUBS fourth graf, ``The two ...., to fix style
on U.N., and sixth graf, The Bush ...., to restore dropped word.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush called French
President Francois Mitterrand on Saturday to discuss coordinating
economic aid for Poland and keeping international attention focused
on peace efforts in Lebanon.
   ``President Bush expressed his concern about the general
situation in Lebanon and reiterated U.S. support for efforts by the
Arab League to resolve the issue,'' according to a statement issued
by the vacation White House.
   A fleet of French warships remained off Lebanon for a possible
evacuation of French citizens.
   ``The two presidents commented on the U.N. (United Nations)
cease-fire in Lebanon and agreed to keep the U.N. spotlight on the
problem.''
   On the subject of Poland, the statement said that the two
presidents discussed the election last week of Solidarity activist
Tadeusz Mazowiecki as Poland's prime minister ``and agreed to
continue offering the support of their two goverments.''
   ``Both presidents want to encourage the new government, while
keeping in mind the delicacy of the situation,'' the statement said.
   The Bush administration has promised Poland $119 million in U.S.
economic aid and is supporting some $325 million in new loans from
international lending agencies.
   The White House statement, quoting Bush directly, said he told
Mitterrand, ``We want to help Poland in a coordinated way. They need
an effective reform program that takes on the economic realities
they face.''
   Vacationing here through Labor Day, Bush also entertained
evangelist Billy Graham on Saturday.
   The president started the day pursuing one of his favorite
vacation activities, ocean fishing. He took out his speed boat
Fidelity in hopes of succeeding where he has so far failed on his 10
days in this coastal resort town. Earlier, he played tennis at his
home on Walker's Point.
   Evening plans called for Bush and his wife Barbara to entertain
some 35 relatives who live in the Kennebunkport area.
   Bush's son Jeb from Florida and his wife and children also were
visiting.
   By Saturday, the president had yet to catch a fish despite daily
excursions onto the water. On Friday his Secret Service body guards
agreed to keep their protective boats and the media chase boats
further away so as not to scare away a prospective catch.
   Graham and his wife were the latest in a stream of guests at
Walker's Point since Bush's arrival Aug. 16. The Grahams and Bushes
were expected to attend church services together Sunday.
   All of the president's five children and their families have been
on hand for several days. The Bushes this past week entertained
Danish Prime Minister Poul Schlueter and his wife Anne Marie for an
overnight visit.
   In addition, several friends have joined the president for golf,
dinner and tennis.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney is scheduled to arrive
here Wednesday for what is billed as a personal, social occasion
rather than a working visit.
   Bush has been receiving daily intelligence briefings while on
vacation and has conducted routine business, but mostly spends his
time at golf, tennis, running and boating.
</TEXT>
