<FIRST>u a AM-SnowmobileShooting Bjt   08-26 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Snowmobile Shooting, Bjt,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>10-Year-Old Boy Moves Toward Adult Homicide Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WLK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STROUDSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defendant wriggled in his chair,
hiking his elbows onto the armrests. He crossed his arms when he
stood before the judge, who called him Mr. Kocher and told him he
had been charged with shooting a 7-year-old girl in the back with a
hunting rifle.
   Cameron Kocher pleaded innocent, moving closer to becoming
apparently the youngest person ever in the country to be tried on an
adult homicide charge. He is 10.
   The boy let out a heavy sigh as he turned to his parents, Keith
and Patricia Kocher, after his arraignment ended Friday.
   Prosecutors have ruled out the death penalty if the the
fourth-grader is convicted. Mark Pazuhanich, a Monroe County
assistant district attorney, said life in prison remains a
possibility, though he hasn't decided yet what punishment he would
seek. No trial date has been set.
   Cameron's lawyer said prosecutors, who fought a request to move
the case to juvenile court, should realize they are not dealing with
``a miniature adult.''
   ``He doesn't understand the concept of murder and doesn't fully
understand the concept of death,'' Charles Hansford said after the
arraignment. ``I don't know how to prepare him.''
   Cameron is charged with killing a playmate, first-grader Jessica
Carr. She died March 6, two months before Cameron's 10th birthday,
after she was shot as she rode on the back of a snowmobile.
   Schools were closed that day because of heavy snow. Cameron,
Jessica, 13-year-old Shannon Ratti and other children were spending
the day playing video games at Shannon's house in Kresgeville, a
town of 250 people in the foothills of the Pocono Mountains.
   After Shannon's father, Richard Ratti, found dirty dishes in the
house, he put the video games off limits, and the children went
outside to ride snowmobiles. But Cameron's parents had told him not
to ride snowmobiles when they weren't around, and he left the house
angry and went to his home next door, Ratti testified.
   The boy said the shooting was an accident while he was playing
with a gun. But investigators gave this account of what happened
next, ticking off a list of deliberate steps that the judge cited in
his decision to have the boy tried as an adult:
   Cameron took a key from under a lamp in his parents' bedroom and
opened his father's gun cabinet, took out a .35-caliber Marlin
lever-action hunting rifle his father had taught him to shoot, and
loaded it.
   After unlocking a bedroom window and opening it, Cameron took out
the screen and set it aside, and he pointed the rifle out the
window, investigators said.
   At 1:05 p.m. a shot rang out, and Jessica, about 100 yards away,
fell from the back of the snowmobile Shannon was driving.
   The rifle's recoil slammed the scope into Cameron's face, cutting
his forehead. Cameron put the rifle back in the cabinet, bandaged
his forehead and hid a spent shell casing.
   Fearing a sniper was on the loose, Ratti called Cameron and told
him to come back to his house for safety. Ratti's wife, Trudy,
testified that Cameron explained the bandage on his forehead by
saying he cut himself with a knife when a dog jumped on him as he
made a peanut butter-and-jelly sandwich.
   As others frantically tried to help Jessica, Cameron sat on the
Rattis' floor and resumed playing the video game, Ratti testified.
Cameron kept playing the game while the other children prayed and
made get-well cards for the girl.
   ``If you don't think about it, you won't be sad,'' Ratti quoted
Cameron as saying.
   The girl was pronounced dead about an hour after she was shot.
Cameron was arrested two days later after investigators found his
blood on the rifle.
   Cameron told psychotherapists he was playing ``hunter'' when he
was looking through the gun's scope and the rifle accidentally
fired. He said he couldn't see anything through the scope but snow
and trees, Dr. Robert Sadoff, a psychiatrist who examined Cameron
for the court, has testified.
   A ballistics specialist testified the rifle could not have
discharged accidently unless a severe blow to the rifle forced the
hammer to strike the firing pin.
   Citing Cameron's apparent mental stability, above-average grades
and the deliberate actions he allegedly took before and after the
shooting, Monroe County Judge Ronald Vican in June refused to move
the case from criminal court to juvenile court. Hansford has
appealed.
   Pazuhanich said the case, one of two murders in the county this
year, troubles him.
   ``I'm preoccupied with how the boy is reacting to the process.
I'm preoccupied by the tension that's in that neighborhood when you
have the Rattis and the Kochers living side by side and the Carrs
still visit the Rattis and everybody is in close proximity to one
another,'' he said.
   ``You wonder, as I'm sure the Carrs do, what was going through
his head and what to do.''
</TEXT>
