<DOCNO> AP890826-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 1448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghan-Jalalabad     08-26 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Jalalabad,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>War-Torn Jalalabad Struggles To Recover</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Jalalabad has been under siege ever since Soviet
troops withdrew early this year. The pressure from guerrillas has
eased somewhat, but Jalalabad remains a city on edge. An Associated
Press reporter visited Jalalabad last week.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JALALABAD, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As this city tries to return to
normalcy after six months on the front line of the Afghan war, the
frequent boom of heavy weapons serves as a reminder that guerrillas
are still around.
   Schools, shops and factories are open again, but Jalalabad is a
shadow of the legendary garden city beloved by Afghan kings for its
Mediterranean climate and leisurely lifestyle.
   This strategic city on the road from Kabul to Pakistan is
shell-pocked, but officials say the worst is over and there is
widespread longing for peace.
   Since Soviet troops withdrew from Afghanistan on Feb. 15,
Jalalabad has been the main battleground for the Soviet-backed
government and U.S.-backed guerrillas trying to topple it and set up
an interim government in the city.
   The rebels failed to take Jalalabad, 45 miles from Pakistan,
after nearly 10 weeks of the most intense bombardment of the war in
April and May. Government troops then pushed the guerrillas back
along the main highway that leads to Pakistan, beyond the strategic
crossroads of Samarkhel.
   Local officials took reporters to Samarkhel, nine miles southeast
of Jalalabad, which government forces captured from the guerrillas
in mid-June. It had been the most significant gain of the rebels,
who call themselves mujahedeen or Islamic Holy Warriors.
   There were no sounds of gunfire in Samarkhel, and government
soldiers lounged under the few trees seeking shelter from the
noon-day sun and smoking an occasional cigarette.
   On the yellow, shell-pocked wall of a building once used as a
transport office were scrawled the words: ``Interim government of
Afghanistan. The hero mujahedeen of Afghanistan.''
   An arch over the road said: ``Long live the Afghan-Soviet
friendship.''
   Government officials refused to show reporters the Samarkhel
garrison, at the foot of a rocky ridge about 2{ miles away, for what
they said were strategic reasons. Although the government claims its
troops occupy the garrison, the guerrillas claim it is a no-man's
land.
   The ridge itself is the last natural line of defense preventing
the government from moving on the main guerrilla areas nearer to the
Pakistani border. Lt. Gen. Manok Mangall, governor of Nangarhar
province which includes Jalalabad, said ``the important and
significant spots'' were in government hands. But Western reporters
on the trip said they had climbed the ridge recently with the
guerrillas who controlled it.
   The guerrillas say controlling this ridge will enable them to
launch a successful offensive against the Samarkhel-based government
troops once they restock their weapons and ammunition supplies. The
loss of Samarkhel has made it infinitely more difficult for the
guerrillas to accurately launch their main short-range missiles
against Jalalabad and its airport.
   In recent weeks, the airport's gravel runway has been repaired,
and reporters flew to Jalalabad on a fixed-wing Antonov 32 rather
than by helicopter. But the flight was at night, in complete
blackout to minimize risks of a mujahedeen attack.
   Mangall, who is chairman of the Afghan Defense Council, said
there were 12,000 armed guerrillas in Nangarhar now, but two-thirds
were not fighting.
   ``Every night, I am negotiating with two or three (guerrilla)
commanders,'' he said. ``Most of them are tired of war.''
   The highly decorated general said the guerrillas have given up
their plan to transfer their interim government to Jalalabad from
Pakistan, ``and the reconstruction of Jalalabad is accelerating.''
   At Bayazid Roshan University and the Nangarhar teacher's training
institute, which reopened last month after a three-month break,
classes were very small and many classrooms were empty.
   A small nucleus of shops have reopened, but in the crowded
marketplace, three out of four shops remained shuttered, a sign of
continuing uncertainty about the future.
   The sounds of outgoing artillery fire and missiles and even a few
incoming rockets are largely ignored. But the effects of the 840,000
rockets and other heavy artillery which Mangall said had hit
Jalalabad during 42 days at the height of the siege are not
forgotten.
   During a brief shopping tour in the bazaar, 22-year-old Takar,
who lost three members of his family in rocket attacks five months
ago, heard there was an American journalist around and stopped his
bicycle to say:
   ``I hate the American government because they are assisting
opposition groups in our city. They are killing our people. We want
peace to come to Afghanistan.''
   At the teacher's training school, 18-year-old Adilla Dehquanzadeh
said she wanted to ask President Bush why the Americans are arming
the mujahedeen.
   ``If I met him, I would ask him not to equip the opposition with
new weapons, not to kill our innocent people, especially our
children, and to support national reconciliation,'' she said.
</TEXT>
