<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     08-26 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Fighting Diminishing After Soviet Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Syrian forces battled with
rockets and artillery on Saturday, but a police spokesman said
hostilities have diminished since a Soviet envoy began a peace
mission in the ravaged country.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing rules,
said two people were killed and nine wounded in the clashes. Scores
of shells and rockets crashed in residential neighborhoods on both
sides of Beirut's dividing Green Line.
   The new casualties brought the overal toll to 796 killed and
2,231 wounded since fighting broke out March 8 between the
traditionally pro-Western Christians and Syrian troops.
   The spokesman noted that the exchanges were ``limited to two
areas, which reflects the noticeable decrease in the intensity and
scope of the shelling duels'' since Soviet envoy Gennady Tarasov
began his mission on Wednesday.
   It was Moscow's first direct mediation in Lebanon since the civil
war broke out in April 1975.
   Tarasov visited Syria, Moscow's chief Arab ally, where he met
with Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa on Wednesday. He drove to
Beirut Thursday and met for two days with Moslem and Christian
leaders, including Gen. Michel Aoun, commander of Christian army
units with whom Syria has refused to negotiate a peace settlement.
   Tarasov, who heads the Middle East Department at the Soviet
Foreign Ministry, returned to Damascus on Friday and was expected to
fly home this weekend for consultations with Kremlin leaders.
   His mission coincided with a French naval buildup off Lebanon.
   Paris said it sent a six-ship flotilla to the Eastern
Mediterranean on a ``humanitarian mission'' to evacuate 7,000 French
nationals if the situation worsens.
   But Syria's Moslem allies and the fundamentalist Hezbollah, or
Party of God, said the move was tantamount to a military
intervention, and vowed to attack any vessel that approaches the
coast.
   After his meeting with Aoun on Friday, Tarasov said the Soviet
Union ``strongly believes there are no military solutions to the
Lebanese problems.''
   Aoun, a spokesman said, expressed to Tarasov his ``full readiness
to cooperate with the Soviet effort.''
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Tarasov
was working on ``a formula ... for stabilizing the security
situation and lifting the blockade'' imposed by Syria and its allies
on the 310-square-mile Christian heartland.
   Asked whether Aoun would accept the deployment of observers at
Christian ports to prevent arms supplies form reaching Aoun, as
demanded by the Moslems, the source said: ``Would the other side
accept observers to prevent the flow of weapons from Syria?''
   A Moslem source said the Soviet diplomatic effort ``did not
contradict'' the deployment of French warships in the Mediterranean.
   ``The Soviet effort is the carrot and the French naval buildup is
the stick,'' the source said, also insisting on anonymity.
   He said the French flotilla in the Mediterranean was ``a
message'' to the Syrians and their allies that ``storming the
(Christian) enclave is not permitted.'' He said the Soviets agree
with that.
</TEXT>
