<FIRST>r a AM-Lutherans     08-26 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutherans,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lutherans Hit Sexual Harassment Of Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America
lashed out Saturday at widespread sexual harassment of women and
called on congregations to make sure their churches are free of such
mistreatment.
   At one point at the church's governing assembly, women who had
experienced harassment were asked to stand, and about 40 of
aproximately 300 women among 1,000 delegates did so.
   The Rev. Judith Gerlitz of New York City said that while sexual
harassment and abuse has spread in the country, ``the church has
done little about it.''
   Some denominations have done surveys finding the problem
extensive even among church personnel and have initiated
countermeasures. The assembly here added its stern voice on the
matter.
   The church ``will not tolerate any forms of sexual abuse or
harassment by any of its personnel,'' the assembly declared, and
pledged to make ``our church a safe place for all persons'' by
moving firmly against such abuses.
   The 5.3-million-member denomination called for looking into the
problem at various church levels and creation of procedures for
victims to report incidents and also to provide ``healing for
victims.''
   ``Sexual violence of many kinds is widespread in our society,''
including ``sexual harassment on the job, rape and sexual assault,
incest and child abuse,'' the resolution said.
   It estimated two-fifths of working women have been sexually
harassed and a third of children sexually abused before 18.
   Such abuses ``betray God's creation, inflict grievous suffering
... and rend the fabric of the whole community of the people of
God,'' the church said.
   Another action saluted the 20th anniversary of the start of
ordination of women in the three Lutheran branches merged into the
present denomination. It has about 1,000 ordained women among 11,000
clergy.
   Congregations that ``have not experienced the preaching, teaching
or pastoral care of women'' were encouraged to open doors to them.
Active recruitment was urged of women for seminaries and ordination.
   ``The church has made a commitment not to keep a separate role of
silent and second-class women,'' said Christine Myers Crist,
executive director of the church's commission for women.
   That means, she told the assembly, bringing ``the unheard,
unheeded voices of women into full participation.'' Some feel that
is to ``try to destroy men,'' she said. ``No way.''
   In a report, she noted that 60 percent of the church's members
are women. Recalling the example of Jesus in regard to women, the
report said:
   ``Barriers against women were woven into the fabric of the
society in which Jesus lived. But Jesus reached ... across all those
barriers against women,'' ignoring rules against them, putting
Scriptures back in their hands.
   ``He appeared first to women as witnesses to his resurrection,''
the report said.
   The assembly is the first since the 1988 merger of the Lutheran
Church in America, the American Lutheran Church and the Association
of Evangelical Lutheran Churches.
   The eight-day assembly runs through Wednesday.
</TEXT>
