<FIRST>r a AM-OrderConvictions     08-26 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Order Convictions,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Affirms Convictions in Talk Show Host's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The civil rights convictions of white supremacists
David Lane and Bruce Pierce in the murder of radio talk show host
Alan Berg have been upheld by a federal appeals court.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected the defendants'
arguments that they participated in Berg's murder because they hated
the outspoken broadcaster as an individual and not because he was a
Jew. The two had contended their federal civil rights convictions
and 150-year prison sentences should be overturned for that reason.
   ``No reversible error has been demonstrated,'' the appeals court
said in its decision Friday.
   The court also rejected other arguments by the defendants,
including that there was insufficient evidence to convict them and
that their civil rights trial amounted to double jeopardy because
their earlier racketeering trial included testimony about the Berg
murder.
   Lane and Pierce belonged to a group of white supremacists called
The Order. They were convicted by a Denver U.S. District Court jury
in November 1987 of violating the civil rights of Berg, 50, when he
was gunned down in June 1984.
   They were indicted on the civil rights count, of interfering with
a federally protected right resulting in death, because there is no
federal murder charge. State prosecutors had decided there was
insufficient evidence to try the two for murder.
   The two, along with several others, were also convicted of
federal racketeering charges, which included allegations of the Berg
killing, in Seattle in 1985. Their 150-year sentences for the Denver
convictions are to follow their racketeering sentences.
   Pierce was sentenced to 100 years and Lane to 40 years for the
racketeering convictions, which were based on their roles in Berg's
death, bank robberies and counterfeiting.
   Witnesses had testified that the murder was triggered by Berg's
on-air derision of the defendants' right-wing beliefs.
</TEXT>
