<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Espionage     08-26 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Espionage,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Reportedly to Charge Former U.S. Soldier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magazine said Saturday that
federal prosecutors are preparing to charge a former U.S. soldier
with treason for his alleged role in a spy ring that sold NATO
secrets to the Soviets.
   The Hamburg-based Der Spiegel magazine said it would be the first
time in West German history that a foreigner faced such charges.
   According to the Spiegel report, federal prosecutors in Karlsruhe
are concluding an investigation and preparing to charge Clyde Lee
Conrad with high treason.
   Conrad remains in investigative custody in a West German prison
following his arrest in August 1988.
   Under West German law, the 42-year-old former soldier would face
a maximum 10-year prison sentence if convicted on spying charges.
However, he could be sentenced to life in prison if convicted of
high treason.
   The federal prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe was closed Saturday,
and officials could not be reached immediately to comment on the
report.
   Der Spiegel did not say when Conrad would be charged.
   In February, prosecutors said their investigation of Conrad had
showed that NATO strategies were damaged more than they thought when
he was arrested.
   Authorities suspect Conrad acted as ringleader of an
international spy network that sold the Soviets information about
the Western alliance's nuclear missiles, bases, and troop strengths.
   Prosecutors believe Conrad, who had access to secret documents
before retiring from the Army in 1985, collected more than $1
million for peddling the secrets.
   Spiegel said the former sergeant is suspected of selling the
Soviets secret rocket codes for nuclear weapons on West German soil.
   Conrad was in charge of keeping classified NATO documents, which
were held in a safe at the Bad Kreuznach base.
   News reports at the time of Conrad's arrest said he had hired
other U.S. soldiers to obtain information. The material was was
passed by couriers to a Hungarian intelligence officer in Vienna,
Austria, and then on to the Soviets, according to the reports.
</TEXT>
