<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TowTruckParade     08-26 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tow Truck Parade,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tow Truck Drivers Line Up for Recognition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It could be tough to find a tow truck in
Rhode Island on Sunday, unless the breakdown is somewhere between
the Warwick Mall and the Rocky Point amusement park.
   Tow truck drivers and rigs from nine states are scheduled to
parade between the two sites, hoping to gain a little more respect
from drivers who equate calling a tow truck with visiting the
dentist for root canal work.
   ``It's basically an awareness thing,'' said Lou Pucino of Pucino
Brothers of Rhode Island. His East Greenwich company is a
major-league towing operation with 10 trucks that can handle
everything from Volkswagens to buses.
   ``Sure, you say, `I don't get enough respect' for the work you
do. We do too,'' Pucino said. ``People ridicule us a lot in tough
situations.''
   Pucino presides over the Rhode Island Towing Association this
year and decided it was time to show off. When the association
shifted its annual family outing from a Massachusetts farm to Rocky
Point, he said he thought of the parade, something towing
associations in other states also have done.
   Pucino said he expects nearly 100 gleaming trucks with their
lights flashing and uniformed drivers to roll along in formation.
   ``A lot of people don't realize how sophisticated our business
has become,'' Pucino said. ``As cars have become more sophisticated,
so has our equipment. ... There are no hooks on tow trucks anymore.''
   The new gentler tow truck now uses a sling that slides under the
wheels and lets a car ride on its own suspension, he said.
   A small towing rig can cost $35,000, he said. And the price of
some of the larger ones? If you have to ask, you can't afford it.
   ``We want the people to realize that we are not putting the money
under our mattresses. We're spending it on men and equipment,'' he
said.
   The towing association has 85 members out of about 110 licensed
towers in Rhode Island, but all this sophistication should mean that
motorists won't have to steam on the highway while the tow drivers
enjoy a clambake.
   ``We all have radios nowadays, and cellular phones. Everybody's
in touch,'' Pucino said. ``So hopefully we'll be able to provide the
service on Sunday.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
