<FIRST>u i AM-Mozambique-Rebels     08-26 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mozambique-Rebels,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>19 Reported Killed in Rebel Attack in Mozambique</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels attacked a southern town but
were repelled by government forces, an official report said
Saturday. It said at least 19 people were killed.
   About 200 rebels of the Mozambican Resistance Movement launched
the attack Thursday on Macia, about 55 miles north of the capital of
Maputo, according to the government news agency AIM.
   At least 12 rebels and seven civilians were killed before
government troops forced the guerrillas to retreat, AIM said, citing
the Maputo daily newspaper Noticias. The report said nothing of
government casualties.
   Noticias also reported that other people were killed by rebels
who overran the central town of Laubo on Aug. 19. It did not say
exactly how many people died.
   The rebels have been fighting since 1977 to undermine
Mozambique's leftist government. No government acknowledges
supporting the rebels, who have devastated Mozambique's economy with
hit-and-run attacks on civilian and military targets.
   Rebel leaders and Mozambican clergymen representing the
government of President Joaquim Chissano met in Kenya this month for
preliminary peace talks, but no agreements were reported.
   The war has claimed an estimated 600,000 lives and displaced more
than 1 million people.
</TEXT>
