<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Orthodox     08-26 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Orthodox,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifteen Ultra-Orthodox Arrested For Sabbath Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Saturday detained 15 ultra-Orthodox
Jews on suspicion of attacking cars driven by secular Jews in a
mostly religious Jerusalem neighborhood, a spokesman said.
   The ultra-Orthodox Jews were protesting what they consider a
violation of the Sabbath, the Jewish day of rest lasting from
sundown Friday until sundown Saturday.
   Jewish religious laws forbid any work or money transactions on
Sabbath, and driving a car is considered a form of work.
   Police said 150 to 200 ultra-Orthodox Jews blocked the streets
and attacked motorists in Har Nof neighborhood.
   Thousands of ultra-Orthodox families populate Har Nof, which also
is home to several hundred secular families.
   Police spokesman Uzi Sandouri said 15 ultra-Orthodox suspected of
disturbing public order and an illegal gathering were detained. Six
were teen-agers and three were released after questioning, he said.
   The last major wave of ultra-Orthodox protests in Jerusalem was
in December 1987, when hundreds of religious Jews demonstrated every
Saturday against movie theaters and other entertainment spots
operating on Sabbath.
</TEXT>
