<FIRST>u w AM-SilentMarch     08-26 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Silent March,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nostalgic March Criticizes `Legal Lynching' of Civil Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LaserPhotos WX9, WX10 and WX12 ^By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the somber cadence of muffled drums, an
estimated 35,000 people marched Saturday upon the Supreme Court and
Congress to protest what NAACP Director Benjamin L. Hooks called
``the legal lynching of black America's hope ... to become full
partners in the American dream.''
   The march, aimed at spurring legislative ``remedies'' for four
recent civil rights decisions by the high court, was fashioned in
tone and dress after the historic ``Silent March'' 72 years ago in
New York City. As then, men wore black and women and children wore
white; as then, the marchers kept their lips sealed throughout the
procession.
   The 1917 march of 8,000 people, led by W.E.B. DuBois, down Fifth
Avenue elevated the 8-year-old National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People to the forefront of the then-fledgling
civil rights movement. Saturday's event, which drew nearly every
major civil rights leader in the nation, may have restored that
standing for an organization which lately has been criticized within
the black community as staid and ineffective.
   ``For an organization that's dead, we did pretty good, didn't
we?'' beamed Hooks as he looked upon the throng which gathered at
the East Front of the Capitol for a rally after the silent march.
   Hooks claimed a turnout of 135,000 people; police estimates were
far smaller. The U.S. Park Police put the number of marchers at
35,000; the U.S. Capitol police said the crowd at the rally was
18,500.
   More than 200 civic, church and labor organizations had joined
the NAACP in sponsoring the march. Individuals joining Hooks on the
speaker's dais included the Rev. Jesse Jackson, AFL-CIO President
Lane Kirkland, Joseph Lowery, president of the Sourthern Christian
Leadership Conference, Dorothy Height, president of the Black
Leadership Forum, and dozens of others.
   ``We come, presenting our bodies in silent protest, in a manner
used in 1917 to protest the brutal lynching of black Americans in
this nation,'' said Hooks. ``It is ironic that 72 years later, we
find ourselves marching once more to protest the legal lynching of
black America's hope for a chance to become full partners in the
American dream.
   ``The five justices who voted on four separate occasions to roll
back the clock on civil rights, by their actions, have unraveled the
ropes used by black Americans to climb out of the valleys of
economic segregation.''
   In the view of civil rights lawyers, the four decisions this year
seriously cut into the modern legal gains of minorities,
particularly employment rights. In one case, Patterson vs. McLean
Credit Union, the court sharply limited the power of minority men
and women to sue private parties, including schools, for
discrimatory practices. Similarly, the court's decision in Richmond
vs. J. A. Croson Co. was seen as diluting job set-aside programs _
guaranteeing certain percentages of municipal projects to minority
subcontractors _ and other affirmative action plans.
   March organizers also assailed the decision in Martin vs. Wilks,
which allowed white firefighters in Birmingham, Ala., to attack a
consent decree calling for the promotion of blacks as a case of
``reverse discrimination.'' The fourth ruling, Ward's Cove vs.
Antonio, was criticized as shifting the entire burden of proof in
job discrimination cases to the victims of employer bias.
   Kirkland told the rally at the Capitol that ``the unions march
today because we believe discrimination cannot be eradicated from
our society until there is equal employment opportunity for all
Americans.''
   The Supreme Court has often been the target of major
demonstrations in the capital in recent years. An estimated 325,000
turned out last spring to urge the court to stand by its 1973
decision legalizing abortion. However, the court weeks later
softened that ruling in a case seen as a victory for anti-abortion
forces.
</TEXT>
