<FIRST>r a AM-Congressman-Prostitute     08-26 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressman-Prostitute,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls: Frank's Consitutents Still Supportive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polls published Saturday indicated U.S. Rep. Barney
Frank's constituents still strongly support him despite revelations
about the congressman's relationship with a male prostitute.
   The state Republican Party, meanwhile, called for the
Massachusetts Democrat's resignation. But political observers
predicted Frank, who publicly acknowledged his homosexuality in
1987, would survive the scandal.
   On Friday, Frank, 49, acknowledged he had once paid for sex with
a man he identified as Steve Gobie, then hired him as a personal
aide in an effort to wean him from a life of drugs and prostitution.
Frank said he fired Gobie when he became suspicious that the man was
selling sex from Frank's Capitol Hill apartment.
   Frank said he had been ``victimized'' and predicted voters would
not hold the incident against him.
   The polls _ and a tradition of tolerance in Massachusetts _
appear to back him up.
   A poll of 400 registered voters in Frank's district conducted
Friday night for The Boston Globe and WBZ-TV showed 65.3 percent did
not think Frank should resign, while 22.3 percent did. About 12
percent had no opinion or refused to answer.
   The Boston Herald and WCVB-TV polled 300 of Frank's constituents,
and 56 percent said Frank has ``performed well enough as a
congressman to deserve re-election'' while 29 percent called for his
ouster. Five percent said their view depends on who opposes Frank in
1990.
   Both polls had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percent.
   After publicly acknowledging his homosexuality, Frank won
election to his fifth term in 1988 with 70 percent of the vote in
the state's 4th District, encompassing some Boston suburbs and parts
of southeastern Massachusetts.
   ``It would be worse if it were some kind of a money scandal. His
sex life is well known, so it came as no surprise,'' said Robert
Freysigner, a political science professor at Bradford College in
Haverhill.
   The only other member of Congress to publicly acknowlege being a
homosexual is Rep. Gerry Studds, also a Massachusetts Democrat.
Studds easily won re-election after being censured by the House in
1983 for an affair 10 years earlier with a 17-year-old male House
page.
   The state GOP urged Frank to resign, charging he ``violated the
law,'' ``lied about the situation'' and showed a ``profound lack of
judgment.''
   Alexander Tennant, the party's executive director, said he
believes voters ``will absolutely object to Barney Frank when they
find out he has been using his public position to help a prostitute,
drug dealer and convicted felon.'' The Washington Times reported
Friday that Gobie had been convicted of obscenity, sex and drug
charges.
   But Christopher Bosso, a congressional scholar at Northeastern
University, said Frank's admissions likely would not affect his
reputation as an effective lawmaker.
   ``Power on Capitol Hill is based on two things: seniority and
support from the voters,'' Bosso said. ``Barney Frank is smart, even
those who disagree with him realize he's one of the smartest members
on Capitol Hill.''
</TEXT>
