<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-French     08-26 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-French,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP Stylebook Editor, Administrator Christopher W. French</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christopher W. French, an Associated Press
newsman and administrator for 23 years and editor of the AP
Stylebook since 1980, has died at age 49.
   French's wife, Sarah, discovered his body at their home in this
New York City suburb Friday after returning from a visit to
relatives out of state. The cause of death was not immediately
determined.
   As editor of the AP Stylebook, a 284-page manual that prescribes
word usage, punctuation and other guidelines for news writing,
French was an arbiter of journalistic style for news media across
the nation.
   The Boston-born journalist was a political science graduate of
the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, where he studied
under a Navy scholarship. After four years of Navy service,
including stints as a gunnery, personnel and public relations
officer, he joined the AP in 1966 as a newsman in the news service's
Chattanooga, Tenn., bureau.
   In 1969, he was assigned to Nashville, the main Tennessee bureau.
In 1971-72 he was a political reporter at the Tennessee statehouse
and helped cover the 1972 national presidential campaign, including
the national party conventions. In November 1972 he was named
Nashville state editor, overseeing AP news coverage throughout
Tennessee.
   French transferred in 1974 to the General Desk in New York, the
central AP national news desk, where he worked as a national editor
and supervisor.
   Six years later, he was named AP Stylebook editor. In that
position, which he has recently shared as co-editor, he updated the
manual annually, to include new subject areas and take account of
changing times and usages.
   Among other editorial responsibilities at the General Desk,
French was editor of the AP Industry News Advisory, a compilation of
reports on developments within the news industry that is transmitted
weekly on AP wires.
   Since 1981, he also held the position of General Desk
administrative assistant for technology. In that role, he acted as
liaison between the editorial and technical staffs, and helped
introduce new computer systems into the AP headquarters in New York.
   Besides his wife, the former Sarah Quackenboss, he is survived by
two daughters, Emily and Catherine; by a sister, Suzanne French
O'Brien of Hopkinton, N.H., and by his mother, Thelma Westerling
French of Massachusetts.
   A memorial service will be conducted at 2 p.m. Tuesday at Christ
Episcopal Church in East Norwalk. In lieu of flowers, the family
asked that contributions be made to the donor's charity of choice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
