<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-26 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hot, Muggy Conditions Wilt South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Muggy air combined with high temperatures Saturday to create
dangerously oppressive conditions from the Tennessee Valley across
the lower Mississippi Valley into Texas, and storms drenched parts
of the South with heavy rainfall.
   The warm, humid air edged northward Saturday from the Gulf of
Mexico. Temperatures rose into the 90s from Florida, through the
coasts of Georgia and South Carolina across the Gulf Coast region,
the Tennessee Valley, and the lower Mississippi Valley into the
southern Plains and Kansas, as well as over the desert Southwest.
   The high temperatures and humidity pushed heat indexes above 105
degrees from the Tennessee Valley across the lower Mississippi
Valley into Texas. The heat index, or apparent temperature, is a
measure of heat and humidity sensed by the body.
   A reading above 105 is considered dangerous, especially to those
involved in prolonged outdoor physical activity.
   The temperature reached 95 degrees at Apalachicola, Fla., on
Saturday afternoon, breaking its record high for the day.
   Thunderstorms formed in the humid, unstable air from the upper
and middle Mississippi Valley across the western half of the Ohio
Valley into the Tennessee Valley.
   Some of the storms brought heavy rainfall. More than 1} inches of
rain deluged Lebanon, Tenn. Ashland, Ala., received more than 1\
inches Saturday afternoon.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across the southern
Atlantic Coast states.
   Much of the West had cool temperatures due to a high pressure
system centered over Montana. Readings Saturday afternoon were in
the 50s and 60s from western North Dakota across Wyoming and the
northern Rockies.
   Temperatures in the 50s and 60s were also common across Maine and
northern New England.
   The low temperature in the lower 48 states Saturday morning was
25 degrees at Jackson, Wyo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m.
EDT ranged from 56 degrees at Arcata, Calif., and Crescent City,
Calif., to 101 degrees at Beeville, Texas.
   The forecast for Sunday called for showers and thunderstorms from
the eastern half of the Gulf Coast across the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast states, the Ohio Valley, the upper Great Lakes and
the upper Mississippi Valley into the northern Plains, and scattered
showers and thunderstorms over the northern Rockies and southwest
Texas.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 60s over northern Maine;
the 70s from Washington across the northern Rockies, the upper
Mississippi Valley and much of the Great Lakes region to New
England, along the California coast and the central Rockies; into
the 90s from the southern Atlantic coast and Florida across the Gulf
Coast region, Tennessee and lower Mississippi valleys, the lower
Missouri Valley into the southern Plains, and the interior valleys
of central and northern California; from 100 to 110 through the
desert Southwest and interior valleys of southern California; and in
the 80s across the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
