<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0547 08-26 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0547,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Collaborator Found Hanged in Orange Grove</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th pvs, `At least...' to ADD Saturday's death of 17-year-old
Palestinian to overall count of victims since uprising began. Picks up
11th pvs, `In the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a young Palestinian suspected of
collaborating with Israeli authorities was found Saturday hanging by
the neck in a West Bank orange grove, Arab journalists and Israel
radio said.
   In other developments, Israeli troops shot and killed a
17-year-old Palestinian youth and raided several villages in the
occupied West Bank, Arab reports said.
   The soldiers also battled Palestinian youths who built makeshift
barricades in Gaza City and hurled stones from rooftops, the reports
said.
   In other scattered clashes in the West Bank, seven Palestinians
were shot and wounded by army troops, Arab hospital officials said.
The wounded included a 13-year-old boy with a gunshot in the neck.
   The body of Amen Tayem, 20, was found in an orange grove in the
West Bank town of Qalqilya, Arab journalists said.
   They said Tayem was last seen being led out of his Qalqilya home
by a group of masked Palestinians two days ago. They attributed the
killing to ``security reasons,'' suggesting he was killed as a
suspected collaborator.
   Israel radio explicitly identified the man as a suspected
collaborator. It said he was beaten to death, and his body was later
tied to the electricity pole.
   An army spokesman confirmed the killing and said the motive was
apparently criminal. However, victims hanged in public places have
generally been suspected collaborators. A police spokesman declined
comment.
   A total of 98 Palestinians have been slain by fellow Arabs as
suspected collaborators during the 20-month Palestinian revolt
against Israeli occupation. Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin claimed
the majority of the victims had no links to Israel.
   At least 548 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli soldiers or
civilians in the uprising. Thirty-eight Israelis also have died in
the violence.
   In the village of Deir es-Sudan near Ramallah, an army patrol was
attacked by stone-throwing Arab youths, an army spokesman said, and
an officer opened fire, fatally wounding a 17-year-old Arab. Israel
radio identified the youth as Sami Hassan Adjadji.
   Palestinian journalists said soldiers raided at least three other
villages in the Ramallah area to arrest suspected uprising
ringleaders.
   The army on Saturday also clamped a curfew on the village of
Idna, near the West Bank town of Hebron, after villagers burned
several houses owned by a suspected Israeli collaborator, Arab
reports said.
   Arab journalists said Israeli soldiers raided at least three
villages in the Ramallah area Saturday to search for suspected
leaders of the uprising.
   During the one-hour clash in Gaza City, Arab youths blocked the
street with stone barricades, Arab journalists said. The protesters
also burned tires and threw stones at soldiers from rooftops, they
said.
   Troops responded with gunfire from observation posts atop
buildings, the journalists said.
   The former West Bank governor, reserve Brig. Gen. Ephraim Sneh,
said Saturday that unless peace efforts progressed, ``negative
processes in the field would strengthen and the radical voices .. .
would also increase.
   ``Their policy may become more tough, and they would issue more
radical orders. In the field, people would spontaneously take more
desperate and therefore more dangerous and violent actions,'' Sneh
said on Israel radio.
</TEXT>
