<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Plane     08-26 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Plane,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Sign of Pakistan Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers in airplanes and on foot
searched the icy peaks and steep valleys of the Himalayas Saturday
for a Pakistan plane that disappeared with 54 people on a domestic
flight.
   Dozens of relatives of the 49 passengers and five crew gathered
at Islamabad Airport, where Pakistan International Airlines and the
air force are operating a joint search command for the
propeller-driven Fokker 27 that disappeared early Friday.
   Five helicopters, two Pakistan air force C-130 transports and two
of the airline's planes searched the rugged northern mountains
Saturday, officials said. They were set to resume Sunday.
   ``We haven't got any indication yet of anything,'' said airline
spokeswoman Azra Sultan. ``We have flown 11 search sorties today and
the search parties are still on the ground since yesterday.''
   Poor weather hampered the initial search Friday as clouds dipped
below the 15,000-foot mountain peaks where the Himalayas meet the
equally lofty Korakoram range.
   Pilots reported better visibility Saturday.
   The missing plane took off from the mountain resort of Gilgit for
the 45-minute flight to Islamabad, 175 miles south.
   Airline officials said the last communication from the pilot was
a routine position check seven minutes into the flight.
   At least two foreigners were aboard the flight, airline spokesmen
said, including American free-lance journalist Paul McGorrian, 27, a
former staff writer for the St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times.
</TEXT>
