<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Glasnost     08-26 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Glasnost,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Slams Unofficial Soviet Press, Says Polish Communists Not
Through</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pravda on Saturday accused several unofficial
newspapers that have sprung up under Kremlin reforms of using
Western funds to press for the overthrow of the Soviet government.
   In another attack on liberal trends, the Communist Party daily
also warned Poles that Polish Communists may have suffered a defeat,
but nobody should write their political obituary.
   Pravda called for a crackdown on publications that carry
``systematic and vicious attacks on our party and its leadership.''
   Among targets of Pravda's censure were papers put out by the
self-styled opposition party Democratic Union, an independent
Siberian news agency and unofficial journalists Lev Timofeyev and
Sergei Grigoryants.
   Their press activities, which once would have brought them
constant harassment and arrests, have flourished despite continuing
obstacles under the Kremlin's policy of glasnost, or more openness.
   Commentator Yuri Zhukov listed among his complaints against the
activist journalists ``truly blasphemous attacks on Lenin,''
including pornographic verses.
   He denounced cooperation between unofficial journalists and
Western radio and press, saying their Western support made them the
equivalent of foreign publications put out without permission on
Soviet territory.
   Zhukov also accused many of the unofficial publications of
pirating their paper supplies and the use of copying facilities.
   Under a law passed July 31, calls for the violent overthrow of
the Soviet government are criminal offenses. An earlier version also
banned statements that ``discredited'' the government, but it was
replaced.
   On Poland, Prava said ``extremist-minded people are hurrying to
write off the Polish United Workers (communist) Party'' following
the election of Soldarity member Tadeusz Mazowiecki as Polish prime
minister.
   The newspaper cautioned that discounting the Communists would be
premature, Pravda cautioned. It said the Communists by right are the
most important group in Polish politics.
   Mazowiecki's election Thursday, with support from many Communist
lawmakers, gave the East bloc is first non-Communist leader since
World War II.
   The Soviet government sent an immediate telegram of
congratulations to Mazowiecki. But Pravda's commentary, the most
authoritative to date, cast doubt on whether Mazowiecki can succeed
in breaking Poland's economic decline.
   ``Is this the way out of the labyrinth?'' the newspaper asked. It
never really answered the question.
</TEXT>
