<FIRST>r a AM-GreenhouseGlasnost     08-26 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greenhouse Glasnost,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>US-Soviet Conference Urges Alliance To Fight Global Warming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUNDANCE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and U.S. scientists, politicians and
entertainers on Saturday urged their governments to forge an
``environmental security alliance'' to combat global warming.
   Actor-filmmaker Robert Redford, who co-sponsored the four-day
conference with the Soviet Academy of Science, read a letter to
President Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev:
   ``The United States of America and the U.S.S.R. are the two
largest producers of greenhouse gases'' thought to cause global
warming, Redford said.
   ``We should provide the leadership in the search for common
solutions to the global warming problem as well as for the
environmental security of the world.''
   The letter was signed by Redford and space researcher Roald
Segdeev, head of an 11-member Soviet delegation, who said the two
nations must cooperate to undo the environmental damage they have
incurred.
   ``For the crimes we've committed, as humans on the planet, we are
sentenced to do this job. And I think it is a life-long sentence,''
Segdeev said.
   His comments ended the conference of Soviet and American
scientists, political leaders, environmentalists, filmmakers and
authors. Among those attending were Sens. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and
Tim Wirth, D-Colo.; Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus; astronomer Carl Sagan,
former Interior Secretary Stewart Udall; and cartoonist Garry
Trudeau.
   The attempt at ``greenhouse glasnost'' was not as much a
scientific conference as it was an attempt to ``pass the baton''
from scientists to policy-shapers in both countries, who need to
take action, Redford said.
   During the conference, scientists predicted that the greenhouse
effect, caused by rising levels of atmospheric carbon dioxide and
other gases produced by industrial societies, could raise global
temperatures by 2 to 10 degrees over the next century. That could
alter worldwide weather patterns and cause the melting of the polar
ice caps, flooding coastal regions.
   To combat the rise of carbon dioxide, much of which comes from
the burning of fossil fuels, the letter proposes the two superpowers
form an ``environmental security alliance'' to:
   _Promote energy-efficient technology.
   _Halt production and use by the year 2000 of chlorofluorocarbons,
another group of greenhouse gases, and ``substantially reduce''
carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases.
   _Reduce the rate of worldwide deforestation and start the
planting of trees in unforested areas.
   The letter was accompanied by a conference report detailing
specific strategies for reducing global warming.
   In the past, Redford's Institute For Resource Management, a
private environmental mediation group based at his Sundance resort
in central Utah, has tackled offshore drilling in the Bering Sea,
the construction of power plants in the Southwest and air quality
issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
