<FIRST>r a AM-Newspage-LL-WorldSeries     08-26 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspage-LL-World Series,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trumbull, Conn., Little Leaguers Beat Kaohsiung, Taiwan, 5-2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumbull, Conn., became the first
American team since 1983 to win the Little League World Series,
beating Kaohsiung, Taiwan, 5-2 Saturday behind Chris Drury's
five-hitter.
   Drury, a 5-foot-1{, 126-pound right-hander with a 66-mph
fastball, struck out two, walked four _ two intentionally _ and went
2-for-3 at the plate.
   His Texas-leaguer with two outs and the bases loaded in the
fourth inning scored two runs and opened up a 4-1 lead in the
nationally televised game.
   Drury allowed a run in the top of the fifth, but Ken Martin
answered with a solo home run in the bottom of the inning for
Trumbull, a suburb of Bridgeport, Conn. Marietta, Ga., won the World
Series in 1983.
   In the sixth inning, Drury walked the leadoff hitter but ended
the game with a fly out, strikeout and deep fly to left field as
jubiliant teammates rushed to the mound and hugged the winning
pitcher.
   Lee Chien-Chih, an 86-pound right-handed submarine pitcher, was
relieved after Martin's home run to lead off the fifth. Lee allowed
five runs and six hits, struck out three and walked none.
   Saturday's championship culminated about 12,250 tournament games
worldwide involving about 7,000 All-Stars teams of 11- and
12-year-olds. About 2.5 million youngsters in 33 countries
participate in Little League, founded 50 years ago.
</TEXT>
