<FIRST>r a AM-StealthBomber 1stLd-Writethru a0568 08-26 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Bomber, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0568,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stealth Bomber Has Secretive Third Test Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with flight details, quotes, pilots
names; CORRECT takeoff time to 8:30, sted 8:31. Pickups at 3rd graf pvs,
`She did ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-2 stealth bomber ended
the longest and most secretive of its three test flights over the
Mojave Desert on Saturday with a safe landing here, an Air Force
spokeswoman said.
   The bat-like bomber took off at 8:30 a.m. from Edwards Air Force
Base and landed at 1:06 p.m., four hours and 36 minutes later, said
Capt. Tess Taft.
   Brig. Gen. Richard M. Scofield, program director for B-2 System
Program Office called the bomber's third flight a success. ``We are
extremely pleased with today's mission,'' Scofield said in a
statement.
   The B-2's flight Saturday ``was by far the longest, highest and
fastest'' thus far, said Taft.
   The aircraft flew at 25,000 feet and at speeds of up to 300
knots, or about 345 miles per hour, she said. In the previous two
flights, the bomber never exceeded a height of 10,000 feet, a speed
of 180 knots or two hours in the air.
   ``The primary mission was to check out the systems and see how it
flies,'' she said. ``That's what test flights are for, to go a
little bit higher, fly a little bit faster.''
   As in the earlier test flights, the bomber was piloted by Air
Force Col. Richard S. Couch and Northrop chief test pilot Bruce
Hinds, said Taft.
   She did not have any other details about the flight from the
desert air base 55 miles northeast of Los Angeles.
   The second test flight of the radar-evading B-2 on Aug. 16 was
cut short in midflight because of a hairline crack in the casing of
an accessory drive. The part powers the $530 million jet's
generators and controls and caused oil pressure to drop, Taft said
Friday.
   The bomber's two-hour maiden flight earlier this summer was
termed a success.
   Unlike the previous two test flights, the Saturday flight was not
announced in advance by the Air Force.
   The government has spent about $22.4 billion in the B-2 program,
which is 18 months behind schedule. Congress has balked at the
thought of paying more than $500 million apiece for 132 bombers.
   Shrouded in secrecy for 10 years, Northrop and the Pentagon last
month began an intensive campaign to surmount stealth foes.
   The Pentagon wants $4.7 billion for the bomber in the coming
fiscal year, and it may need $8 billion in each of the three years
of peak production, from 1992 to 1994.
   Engineers say that the use of composite materials, combined with
the bomber's shape and smooth leading edges, give it a tiny radar
signature, making it nearly impossible for current Soviet systems to
detect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890826-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 1927EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nigeria-Universities     08-26 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nigeria-Universities,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Will Allow Universities To Reopen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government announced Saturday
it will allow six universities to reopen Oct. 30, four months after
they were closed because of student riots.
   The six universities had been ordered closed for a year, but
Education Minister Jubril Aminu said the Armed Forces Ruling Council
had decided to accede to pleas by religious and education leaders.
   He said the six universities would be required to skip vacations
to make up for lost time, and students must agree to pay for damage
to university property. He said parents of all enrolled students
will be held responsible for further misconduct.
   A total of 23 university and vocational colleges were ordered
shut immeditately after students and others rioted in June against
strict austerity measures imposed by the government. At least 43
people died in the violence.
   The government has refused to retreat from the austerity program,
required by Western creditors, saying there is no alternative. But
it announced a package of relief measures, including some wage
increases.
   The universities to reopen are in Lagos, Benin, Ibadan, Ekpoma
and Okigwe.
