<FIRST>r a AM-HelmsleyTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0513 08-26 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0513,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deliberations Begin on Helmsley Tax Evasion Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with deliberations ending for day. INSERTS
3 grafs after 5th graf, `Walker also...,' to UPDATE with jury's request
for Helmsleys' personal tax returns, other details. Picks up 6th graf,
`Mrs. Helmsley...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Saturday began deliberating the fate of
Leona Helmsley, who is accused of avoiding taxes by charging
personal expenses to her hotel business.
   The Manhattan federal court jury, which received the case after a
two-month trial at which 48 witnesses testified, deliberated more
than eight hours before breaking for the day. The jurors, who are
sequestered, planned to return at 10:30 a.m. Sunday.
   Soon after they began deliberations, jury foreman Alvin Taylor, a
postal worker, sent out a note asking for 11 copies of the judge's
instruction on the law and the ``court journal.''
   Judge John Walker Jr., who had already given them one copy of the
charge, which he had read to them Friday, refused to supply them
with more. He explained that jurors should do their thinking as a
whole and that he did not want individual jurors reading from
different parts of his instructions.
   Walker also declined to give them the court journal, which he
deduced was the entire trial transcript. He told the jurors that
they would have to ask for testimony from specific witnesses or
about specific issues.
   Later, they sent another note asking for the Helmsleys' personal
tax returns for 1983-85 and a folder of all the records of money
spent on the Helmsleys' Connecticut estate, Dunnellen Hall.
   The jurors also asked for documents pertaining to the moving
expenses of the former houskeeper at the estate, Elizabeth Baum. The
government contends that her moving costs, almost $4,000, were paid
for by the Park Lane Hotel.
   During the deliberations, Mrs. Helmsley chatted with her lawyers
and the reporters covering the trial. She appeared relaxed and
smiled frequently.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, has been on trial for eight weeks on charges
she evaded $1.2 million in federal taxes by charging personal
expenses, including renovations at her Connecticut estate, to her
businesses.
   Former aides Frank Turco and Joseph Licari, who are co-defendants
at the trial, are charged with assisting in the scheme.
   Mrs. Helmsley and Turco also are charged with conspiring to
extort payoffs and merchandise from vendors doing business with the
Helmsley organization.
   Mrs. Helmsley's 80-year-old husband, Harry, was charged in the
indictment but was severed because he was found to be mentally
incompetent.
</TEXT>
