<FIRST>r a AM-Florida-Crackdown 1stLd-Writethru a0549 08-26 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida-Crackdown, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0549,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Roundup Nets 2,100 Arrests, 9,500 Crack Rocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT starting date of first operation to
June 30, sted June 31.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's second statewide crack crackdown this
summer captured more than 2,100 suspects _ from teen-agers to an
82-year-old man _ and more than doubled the number of crack rocks
confiscated, authorities said Saturday.
   The greater quantity of crack seized in ``Operation Rock Pile
II'' indicates police arrested more dealers than in the first
roundup, Broward County sheriff's spokesman George Crolius said.
   An estimated 1,200 officers in all of the state's 67 counties
arrested 2,117 suspects during the 48 hours ending midnight Friday,
compared with 2,076 arrests in the two-day operation begun June 30.
   The second roundup produced 9,507 crack cocaine ``rocks'' _
individual chunks of crack ready for smoking _ as well as 2.73
pounds of cocaine powder, 12.72 pounds of marijuana, 75 firearms,
327 vehicles and more than $70,000 in cash, Crolius said by
telephone from the operation command post in Fort Lauderdale.
   The first ``Operation Rock Pile'' netted 3,510 crack cocaine
rocks, 10 pounds of cocaine powder, 3 pounds of marijuana, 50
firearms, 327 vehicles and $55,000 cash.
   The operations' main objective was to ``get as much crack off the
street as we can,'' said another sheriff's spokesman, Jim Leljedal.
   In Pompano Beach, Frank Wilcher, 82, was among those arrested,
Crolius said.
   Wilcher, who had a substantial amount of crack rocks, cash and
several firearms in his house, was charged with trafficking in
cocaine, and could face a life sentence if convicted, Crolius said.
   ``It's an enticement to all members of our society, the lure of
easy money from the sale of crack rocks,'' said Crolius.
   The crackdown, coordinated by the Florida Sheriffs' Association,
combined reverse sting and ``Trojan Horse'' operations with search
warrants and highway surveillance.
   Undercover officers in reverse stings pose as drug sellers and
arrest customers. In ``Trojan Horse'' operations, deputies hidden in
the back of a van jump out and arrest street corner dealers when
they offer crack for sale to the van's driver.
</TEXT>
