<FIRST>u w AM-Colombia-SecurityWarning     08-26 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Security Warning,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Issues Travel Warning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department, citing Colombia's massive
crackdown on drug traffickers, issued a travel warning Saturday
night and asked Americans to postpone trips to that South American
nation.
   ``Due to recent events, Colombia's security situation is
unsettled and likely to remain so in the near future,'' a statement
read by State Department spokesman Adam Shub said. ``The government
of Colombia's aggressive actions against narcotics traffickers could
raise the level of violence in some areas and American citizens,
even though not specifically targeted, could find themselves caught
up in random violence.''
   An unprecedented crackdown is underway in Colombia following the
recent murder of a highly popular presidential candidate, Luis
Carlos Galan. The Colombians have confiscated millions of dollars in
goods and made mass arrests.
   ``The Department of State recommends that non-essential travel to
Colombia be postponed for at least several weeks, pending
clarification of the security situation. Those who deem their travel
essential should contact the U.S. Embassy in Bogota or the U.S.
Consulate in Barranquilla immediately upon arrival,'' the statement
said.
   Shub said the travel warning was issued following a decision by
the U.S. Embassy in Colombia to limit travel to the country. He said
it was a ``precautionary measure'' aimed at reducing ``the demands
on the embassy security staff.''
   ``There is no evidence of a specific threat against either
official or private Americans, but given the heightened level of
confrontation between the Colombian authorities and drug
traffickers, we believe it is prudent for U.S. citizens to avoid
non-essential travel,'' Shub said.
</TEXT>
