<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak-Clergy,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>More than 15,000 Celebrate Consecration of Bishop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLOMOUC, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 15,000 Roman Catholics
celebrated the consecration Saturday of the first archbishop of
Olomouc in 16 years, the Austrian-based Catholic news agency
Kathpress reported.
   It said 6,000 people watched the consecration of Frantisek Vanak
by Bishop Antonin Liska of Prague on a giant movie screen set in
front of Olomouc Cathedral because the church could not contain the
crowd. Olomouc is 120 miles east of Prague.
   Vanak, 73, in July was elevated from parish priest to bishop.
   Thirteen dioceses remain without bishops in Czechoslovakia,
reflecting strained relations between the Vatican and the communist
leadership.
   Many have been vacant for decades because the two sides cannot
agree on candidates.
   The government prefers clergymen who are members of Pacem im
Terris, an organization usually subservient to the state.
Independent priests frequently complain of official harassment.
   The Vatican says 60 percent of Czechoslovakia's 15 million people
are Catholic.
</TEXT>
