<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Election     08-26 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Election,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Coalition Announces Electoral Platform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 14-party opposition coalition on
Saturday announced a platform for February elections focusing on
Nicaragua's economic crisis but offering no details of a promised
austerity budget.
   The National Opposition Union also promised legal title to
peasants given land under Sandinista agrarian reforms and
compensation for those whose land was confiscated.
   It pledges several improved social programs but does not mention
the tough measures any Nicaraguan government would need to take to
halt inflation and increase production.
   A coalition ``Government of National Salvation'' would institute
an austerity budget, the platform says without detailing specifics.
   President Daniel Ortega's Sandinista government already is taking
some measures. In January, it fired 30,000 public employees, cut its
budget by more than 40 percent and slashed investments to combat
inflation that topped 33,000 percent last year.
   But the Sandinistas have failed to create a climate of confidence
in the private sector to encourage production. Confiscating land as
punishment for political opposition is among Sandinista measures
that have antagonized private business and lowered production.
   That is one area marked for change by the coalition, which spans
a broad spectrum of ideologies range from communist to conservative.
   Its platform envisions less state control of the domestic and
export markets, more foreign investment and a freeing of the economy.
   It also mentions in several places its intent to separate the
armed forces from politics and reduce the size of the 200,000-strong
army _ the largest in Central America.
   The coalition said it will announce its candidates for president
and vice president next week. Coalition members still must decide
the procedure for choosing the candidates.
   Likeliest choices for their presidential candidate are Violeta
Barrios de Chamorro, whose family owns the opposition newspaper La
Prensa; businessman Enrique Bolanos Geyer, and Independent Liberal
Party leader Virgilio Godoy.
</TEXT>
