<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan-Housing     08-26 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-Housing,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>10,000 Protest Soaring Housing Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 people protested in
downtown Taipei Saturday to demand the government curb real estate
prices, which are soaring because of rampant speculation.
   The protesters, claiming they could never afford buying their own
homes under current prices, briefly sat down on several downtown
streets during the three-hour demonstration.
   Lee Hsin-chang, who heads the Houseless People's Union that
organized the demonstration, told the crowd, ``A house is not a
commerical product to be speculated. It is our basic right to own a
house.''
   Organizers cited a government report that says a Taipei apartment
was sold for an average of $460,000 last year, and it would take 19
years of an average family's entire income to buy one. Housing costs
have increased more than 200 percent since 1987.
   The protesters demanded the government establish rent control and
restrict insurance and investment firms from buying houses to quick
resale. They want more public housing and low-interest loans to
first-time buyers.
   Interior Minister Hsu Shui-teh told the Houseless People's
Association Friday the government would consider building more
public housing in suburban areas and setting rental ceilings.
</TEXT>
