<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionProtests 1stLd-Writethru a0587 08-26 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0587,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede COLUMBIA, Mo.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with protest in New Jersey and
NOW rally at Atlantic City; picks up 6th graf pvs, `The clinic ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Protesters Arrested; Abortion Rights Group Marches</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   More than 180 anti-abortion demonstrators were arrested Saturday
during protests in Kansas, Missouri and New Jersey, while 400 people
marched six miles in Atlantic City to demand that politicians
support abortion rights.
   In New Jersey, 137 anti-abortion advocates were arrested in a
demonstration that forced the temporary closing of a Cherry Hill
abortion clinic. Police in Columbia, Mo., arrested 44 anti-abortion
demonstrators who blocked the doors to a Planned Parenthood clinic
for nearly four hours Saturday.
   On the opposite side of the issue, 400 pro-choice demonstrators
turned out for a six-mile walk-a-thon along the Atlantic City
boardwalk. The event was sponsored by the National Organization for
Women and NOW-New Jersey to raise money for the state chapter's
Political Action Committee.
   National NOW President Molly Yard said the march in New Jersey
helped identify candidates for the state Legislature who support the
right to an abortion and would get the word to voters.
   ``Voters in this country do believe that it's up to a woman to
decide what happens to her body,'' Ms. Yard said.
   Referring to the Supreme Court's decision this summer giving
states the right to regulate abortion, Ms. Yard said: ``American
women are very mad about what happened, and they're not going to
take it any more. And there are a lot of men who support that.''
   About 200 anti-abortion advocates protested outside the Cherry
Hill Women's Center early Saturday morning. Those arrested were
charged with defiant trespassing for blocking the center's
entrances, said Police Sgt. Edward Morton.
   At the Columbia, Mo., clinic, police charged the ``Operation
Rescue'' members, most from the Kansas City area, with trespassing
and released them on their own recognizance, said Deputy Chief
Carroll Highbarger.
   Several abortion-rights activists held a counter-demonstration.
``They yelled back and forth, but that was it,'' Highbarger said.
   Women waiting for abortions or to pick up birth control goods
remained in a parking lot across the street until the clinic opened,
said India McCanse, the clinic's community affairs director. Some
were upset, but none left, she said.
   The clinic performs 10 to 12 abortions on a typical Saturday,
McCanse said.
   In the Kansas City suburb of Overland Park, Kan., three people
who attempted to block the entrance to the Comprehensive Health for
Women clinic also were arrested on trespassing charges Saturday.
   Lt. Steve Ford said the three were released on their own
recognizance.
</TEXT>
