<SECOND>AM-Panama,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Closes Opposition Party Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government closed down three
opposition party newspapers Saturday and said it will arrest their
editors and confiscate equipment used to publish them.
   A statement from the Government and Justice Ministry said the
newspapers were published ``to slander and damage leaders of the
national government and its institutions, following the lines of
American imperialism in its aggression against the fatherland.''
   The three newspapers are published by the Authentic Liberal and
Christian Democratic parties and the Liberal Republican Nationalist
Movement.
   All three are among opposition parties calling for the ouster of
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who as chief of the Defense Forces
wields the real power in Panama.
   No arrests were reported Saturday. Opposition leaders did not
immediately comment on the order.
   The communique said the publications violated news media laws but
did not detail alleged offenses.
   It ordered ``the arrest of any person who irresponsibly edits and
sells'' the newspapers.
   ``Far from orienting national public opinion, they do no more
than plant hatred and bitterness in the Panamanian family,'' it said.
   Tension between the government and opposition has been increasing
in recent days. On Friday, the civilian government's term of office
expires.
   The opposition refused a government offer to share power in a
civilian-military junta.
   Foreign observers said the opposition won May 7 elections by a
landslide, but Noriega annulled the balloting. The opposition
demands the May 7 elections be recognized and that Noriega leave.
The government has refused.
   The United States has imposed economic sanctions in an effort to
get Noriega to turn over power. Noriega was indicted by Florida
grand juries on drug trafficking and money laundering charges. He
denies the charges.
