<FIRST>r a AM-SovietNavy     08-26 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Navy,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Navy Could Visit San Diego in 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet warships are tentatively scheduled to
visit San Diego sometime next summer in the first such naval port
visit to the West Coast, a newspaper reported.
   The San Diego Union on Saturday quoted unnamed State Department
and Navy sources as saying the visit will be part of a military
exchange program to include a port visit by U.S. warships to the
Soviet city of Vladivostok.
   No exact date has been set for either visit, the sources said.
   ``We have agreed in principle to a Pacific exchange,'' said a
senior State Department official who works with a State
Department-Defense Department interagency council that proposed the
visits.
   ``We offered the Soviets visits to either San Diego or Honolulu.
It will be San Diego because the Soviets want to visit the U.S.
mainland, and they offered us Vladivostok,'' the Union quoted the
official as saying.
   The newspaper said the official requested anonymity pending a
formal announced by the White House next year.
   The visits would be the second round in a new naval exchange
program created by Adm. William Crowe, the chairman of the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staff, and Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, the Soviet
chief of staff.
   In July, three Soviet warships spent five days at the Norfolk,
Va., Naval Base. Earlier this month, three American warships
carrying about 1,200 sailors visited Sevastopol in the Crimea.
