<FIRST>r a AM-TropicalWeather 2ndLd-Writethru a0578 08-26 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0578,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixth Tropical Storm Forms Off Africa; Erin Losing Strength</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-5, bgn `At 6 p.m....,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
10:30 p.m. EDT data. Picks up 6th graf, `Erin posed...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Kiko</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sixth named tropical storm of the Atlantic
season formed off the African coast Saturday as its predecessor,
Erin, withered in cooler northern waters, forecasters said.
   Felix, with maximum sustained winds of 40 mph, was expected to
intensify as it moved westward, according to forecasters at the
National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT Saturday, Felix's center was near 17.7 north
latitude and 24.1 west longitude, or about 90 miles northwest of Sal
in the Cape Verde Islands, moving toward the west at about 8 mph.
   Erin, which was downgraded from a hurricane on Saturday, was
centered near 53.0 north latitude and 30.5 west longitude, or about
800 miles west of Ireland, at 10:30 p.m. EDT and moving toward the
northeast near 35 mph.
   Erin's strongest winds were clocked at 55 mph and a continued
decrease in strength was forecast.
   Erin posed no threat to land and was expected to lose its
tropical characteristics as it moved over colder waters, the center
said.
   ``It looks like it's going downhill,'' said meteorologist Jack
Beven. The center predicted the storm was heading somewhere between
Greenland and Ireland.
   Erin was the third hurricane of the Atlantic season, which runs
from June 1 to Nov. 30. Spawned off the African coast, it reached
hurricane strength Tuesday, three days after becoming a named storm.
   A tropical depression becomes a named storm when sustained winds
reach 39 mph and a hurricane if winds climb to 74 mph.
   In the Pacific Ocean, meanwhile, Hurricane Kiko roared toward
northern Mexico's Pacific coast Saturday, packing winds near 110
mph. Residents of Baja California Sur were bracing for the storm.
</TEXT>
