<FIRST>r a AM-TankerSpillClaim     08-26 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill Claim,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Claiming Spill Damage Wins Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fisherman won a $7,700 settlement from
Exxon and Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. after filing a complaint in
small claims court that he lost wages because of the nation's
largest oil spill.
   Chris Daniels, 38, filed a $4,800 claim against each company
March 27, three days after the tanker Exxon Valdez tanker hit a reef
in Prince William Sound and spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil.
   On Friday, a five-hour conference in the office of Anchorage
District Court Judge Glen Anderson ended with Exxon and Alyeska
writing $7,700 in checks to Daniels. He dropped his demand for a
letter of apology from Don Cornett, the head of Exxon in Alaska.
   Daniels said he lost nearly $10,000 because the oil spill left
fishermen unable to fish, and left him without people for whom to
hang nets. His earnings would have allowed him to rent a boat for a
fishing venture that would have generated $100,000, he said.
   Daniels said he went to court because Exxon made him a
take-it-or-leave-it offer of only $500. An Exxon attorney said the
company had trouble getting paperwork from Daniels.
   The corporations argued in court papers that Daniels, a Cordova
resident, raised issues too complicated to be decided by a
magistrate there. They requested that the case be dismissed.
   Daniels resisted and threatened to subpoena oil industry
executives to the Prince William Sound fishing town. The
corporations then asked that a settlement conference be held in
Anchorage, with Daniels on the telephone in Cordova 150 miles away.
   He chose to catch a flight to Anchorage and appeared at the
courthouse Friday.
</TEXT>
