<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-Japan     08-26 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Japan,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italy Abolishes Import Quotas For Japanese Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy lifted import quotas on some Japanese goods
Saturday in the first of a series of steps to liberalize trade
between the two countries, the Italian news agency ANSA said.
   Foreign Trade Minister Renato Ruggiero has lifted the quotas on
such items as clothing, bulk silk imports and canned tuna and
sardines, the agency reported.
   ANSA said quotas for cars, motorcycles and electronic devices
remain unchanged.
   Ruggiero's action is the first in a four-stage plan to liberalize
trade with Japan. In January, Italy is to lift quotas on Japanese
ceramics, in January 1991 on Japanese film products and a year later
those on steel products and tires.
   Saturday's decree also lifted quotas on cutlery, motors except
those for cars, batteries and different kinds of toys.
