<FIRST>u i AM-PuertoRico-Macheteros 1stLd-Writethru a0599 08-26 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico-Macheteros, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0599,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Independence Militant Innocent of Assault Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE wtih Ojeda Rios' and judge's
comments. CORRECTS trial length from four to five weeks. Pickup 7th pvs,
``Ojeda Rios ...'' SUBS 3 grafs for last pvs, `Puerto Rico...' to ADD background
on debate on island's future status. ^By JULIO GHIGLIOTTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury on Saturday night
declared independence militant Filiberto Ojeda Rios innocent of all
charges filed against him for shooting at FBI agents during his 1985
arrest.
   ``This has been a historic verdict. A message of powerful content
to the United States government,'' Ojeda Rios told hundreds of
well-wishers outside the federal building. ``I was tried by their
court ... but by Puerto Ricans, and they lost!''
   But U.S. District Judge Carmen Consuelo Vargas de Cerezo said she
could not free Ojeda Rios since he still is wanted in Hartford,
Conn., for his alleged part in a $7 million Wells Fargo robbery
there in 1983.
   Defense attorney Luis Camacho said Ojeda Rios probably will be
transferred to Roosevelt Roads Naval Station in eastern Puerto Rico,
and eventually be flown to Hartford.
   The 12-member jury issued the verdict after more than four hours'
deliberation.
   Ojeda Rios, self-proclaimed leader of the pro-independence
Macheteros underground group, had faced charges for shooting at
federal agents during his 1985 arrest at his home in Luquillo,
Puerto Rico. FBI agent Abelardo Alba was slightly injured when
struck by a bullet fragment in the eye.
   The five-week trial, in which Ojeda Rios defended himself, ended
Thursday.
   The jury dropped all eight charges, including assault, illegal
arms possession and preventing federal agents from carrying out an
arrest.
   Ojeda Rios claimed he acted in self-defense when he opened fire
with his Uzi submachine gun, alleging the FBI agents who raided his
home shooting their weapons intended to kill him.
   ``I could reach no other conclusion,'' Ojeda Rios told the jury.
``They tried to assassinate me.''
   He said he had been under FBI surveillance for weeks and could
have been arrested at any time, making the raid unnecessary.
   Ojeda Rios acknowledged he burned documents moments before the
federal agents burst into his apartment, but said it was to protect
the identity of other Puerto Rican independence militants.
   U.S. District Attorney Daniel Lopez Romo told the jury that those
activists were not ``innocent believers in the noble ideal of
independence.'' He said Ojeda Rios burned the documents to protect
Puerto Ricans involved in illegal activities.
   During the trial, FBI witnesses claimed they warned Ojeda Rios to
surrender before deciding to raid the apartment.
   The FBI arrested Ojeda Rios and several other Macheteros members
in an islandwide sweep on Aug. 30, 1985.
   Sixteen Puerto Ricans allegedly took part in the Wells Fargo
robbery, including seven who were sentenced earlier this year. The
State Department claims the main suspect in the robbery, Wells Fargo
security guard Victor Gerena, escaped to Cuba with part of the loot.
   Ojeda Rios is expected to stand trial on the robbery charges at a
later date.
   The trial came in the midst of heated debate of the island's
relationship with the United States, which took control of Puerto
Rico after the 1898 Spanish-American war.
   Draft legislation for a 1991 plebiscite on the island's future
recently has been prepared. The options are statehood, independence
or continued commonwealth status with more autonomy for its 3.2
million people. In a 1967 plebiscite, the Spanish-speaking Caribbean
island chose commonwealth status.
</TEXT>
