<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Steel-SouthAfrica     08-26 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel-South Africa,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Steel Deal Violates Trade Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas congressman asked the Treasury
Department Friday to investigate a Customs Service ruling he says
would allow U.S. companies to import South African steel for
construction of a bridge across the Houston Ship Channel.
   Bryant, a Democrat, said the decision by Customs' Commercial
Rulings Division appears to go against the Anti-Apartheid Act of
1986, which prohibits the importation of South African steel and
iron into the United States.
   According to Bryant, the ruling would allow two contractors hired
by the Texas Highway Department, Williams Brothers of Houton and
Traylor Brothers of Indiana, to import nearly 3.1 million pounds of
steel from a South African company for the bridge project.
   Customs spokeswoman Judy Turner in Houston said the agency was
not prepared to comment late Friday on Bryant's inquiries. She said
she could not confirm the substance of the ruling and officials at
the division were not available for comment late Friday.
   The $91 million bridge would be the costliest state funded road
work in Texas history.
   According to Bryant, the ruling was issued July 14.
   ``Considering the fact that President Bush, the Congress, and
many other public officials both statewide and nationally have have
gone on record opposing the inhumane system of apartheid and the
purchase of materials derived from the exploitive use of cheap
leabor, I cannot even begin to comprehend this decision,'' said
Bryant.
   Bryant has also asked Robert H. Dedman, chairman of the Texas
Highways and Public Transportation Commission, for an explanation.
   ``I am at a loss to understand why the Highway Commission would
apparently not only pass over the American steel industry and its
workers, but also indirectly support South Africa's apartheid
government,'' Bryant wrote Dedman.
   Bryant has asked Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady to determine
whether the Commercial Rulings Division has the jurisdiction to make
such a ruling, and on what basis it made its decision. He also wants
to known when the contract was signed, the name of the South African
company, and whether the ruling violates the Anti-Apartheid Act of
1986 or any other laws on trade with South Africa.
   The Anti-Apartheid Act of 1986 is aimed at curtailing U.S. trade
with South Africa because of that country's system of racial
separation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890826-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-89 0014EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CFTC-SoybeanSqueeze     08-26 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CFTC-Soybean Squeeze,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Sees No Conflict in CBOT Soybean Emergency; Senator Skeptical</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version has run on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission said
Friday that it found no examples of self-dealing by officials of the
Chicago Board of Trade during last month's forced liquidation of
soybean futures contracts.
   But the chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee said a
preliminary report by the commission raised possible
conflict-of-interest questions about several of the officials who
voted to require traders to reduce their holdings of contracts
calling for future delivery of soybeans to them _ ``long'' positions.
   ``The CFTC must question those Chicago Board of Trade directors
participating in the July soybean decision whose affiliated firms
held net short positions in the July soybean contract in house or
customer accounts,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., in a statement
issued by his office.
   ``Credibility is paramount for exchanges in carrying out their
self-regulatory functions. The public will not tolerate self-dealing
or conflict of interest by exchange directors or insiders,'' the
Leahy statement said.
   Holders of ``short'' positions, promises to deliver beans they do
not own, would benefit from an order like the one issued by the
Board of Trade on July 11.
   One who holds a short position can can buy and deliver beans, or
he can buy an offsetting ``long'' position. Generally such a trader
is betting on a fall in price and the ability to buy an offsetting
contract at a price lower than he paid for his original contract,
thus making a profit.
   If the ``longs'' are forced to sell, the price of the contract
declines and the ``shorts'' can fulfill their obligations cheaper
than they would otherwise.
   The order forcing ``longs'' to sell touched off wild swings in
soybean prices and sparked sharp criticism by farm groups and
traders who saw the value of their holdings drop.
   The Board of Trade has said it acted after consulting the
commission because Italian grain merchant Ferruzzi Finanziaria
S.p.A., failed to reduce its large holdings in the July soybean
market voluntarily.
   Officials of the exchange have said they were worried that there
were not enough beans to fulfill all delivery commitments in the
final days of the contract.
   The order required traders to reduce their long positions to 1
million bushels and was widely perceived as a move to prevent
Ferruzzi from cornering the market _ that is, forcing other traders
into a position of having to deliver beans to Ferruzzi where
Ferruzzi was the only source of beans.
   Such a situation, if Ferruzzi could maintain it, would all but
enable Ferruzzi to name its own price to let the other traders off
the hook. Stock and commodity exchanges have rules aimed at banning
``corners.''
   Ferruzzi has denied any wrongdoing or intention to corner the
market and has bitterly critized the board's action.
   ``We continue to believe that is was totally unnecessary for the
board to take its emergency action,'' said David Swanson, an
executive with Ferruzzi Group, a U.S. subsidiary.
   ``The Ferruzzi Group supports Sen. Leahy's call for further
investigartion by the CFTC into the matter.''
   Michael Oakes, a spokesman for the exchange, said that even
though directors may have represented firms whose customers held
short July soybean positions ``they're not involved in the
decision-making of their customers.''
   The commission said it found no director who appeared to trade
for the purpose of profiting personally, or through an affiliated
firm, from prior knowledge of the July 11 order.
   One director excused himself before deliberations began because
he held a spread position _ both long and short _ in July soybeans.
His affiliated firm also had net short positions for itself and
customers.
   The commission's preliminary report was contained in a 36-page
letter to Leahy from Chairwoman Wendy L. Gramm. It said
investigators intend to conduct more interviews.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
