<FIRST>r i AM-France-HighWire     08-26 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-High Wire,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petit To Fulfill Dream, Walking Wire To Eiffel Tower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippe Petit hopes his high-wire walk to the
Eiffel Tower on Saturday will lift the hearts of the thousands
watching, inspire them to try the impossible and demonstrate real
freedom as France celebrates justice and liberty.
   Petit, known for his illicit and joyous walks between the towers
of Paris' Notre Dame Cathedral and New York's World Trade Center,
said Friday he is ready for the walk that will take him 2,300 feet
from the Palais de Chaillot to the Eiffel Tower's second level.
   ``I'm impatient to begin, to do something I've dreamt of doing my
whole life,'' said Petit, who was born 40 years ago in a suburb west
of Paris and now lives in New York.
   Rushing between the barber and a technical check of the rigging,
the aerialist took a moment to reflect on the spectacle that is a
highlight of French celebrations commemorating the bicentennial of
the Declaration of the Rights of Man.
   ``People hear the word funambulist and they think of the circus,
but that's not at all what I do,'' he said, gazing at the wire
strung fine as a spider's web.
   ``I want people to be enlightened by a vision, I want to uplift
their minds and hearts.''
   Petit, who shares with dancers a passion for poetic gestures and
movements that transfigure, is asked with deadly monotony about the
danger involved in his work. The question bores him.
   ``I take no risks. I've been preparing for this for 10 years and
the technical aspects for six months,'' said Petit, who did all his
own rigging and studied blueprints, photos and charts.
   His walk was authorized by Paris Mayor Jacques Chirac who will be
waiting on the tower's second level, 330 feet above the ground.
Petit will carry a rolled copy of the Declaration of the Rights of
Man on his 40-pound balancing bar to lay in Chirac's hands.
   The document, distilling ideals of liberty and social justice
that emerged in 1789 from the French Revolution, doesn't interest
Petit. He wants to present his own vision.
   ``When you see someone who does something seemingly impossible,
it must be that anything is possible. I want to tell people, 'Your
dreams can come true. Not by luck but by shovel and ax.'
</TEXT>
