<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions Aug. 26-27</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sugar Prices Swing Between Sweet and Sour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar futures prices fluctuated widely on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange as traders bought into the market on news of
a large purchase by India and bailed out on reports the European
sugar beet crop may exceed last year's.
   Adding to sugar price instabilty is what analysts say is the
inability of the October futures contract to sustain advances at a
price higher than 14 cents a pound.
   Bernard Savaiko, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York,
said traders view the sugar market as bullish, but are afraid to buy
contracts.
   He said there won't be a significant change in trader attitudes
until Third World countries are willing to pay high prices created
by the delicate balance of supply and demand.
   World sugar stocks are low due to several years of poor
sugar-cane crops and steadily rising consumption.
   Savaiko said a factor keeping Third World countries out of the
sugar market is that sugar is often bought and sold for dollars,
making it expensive in terms of those country's currencies.
   A Third World leader, India, entered the market for 200,000 tons
of refined sugar. But it had been expected that India would purchase
as much as 500,000 tons of raw and refined sugar, so the smaller
figure was a disappointment.
   Sugar prices fell sharply on projections by F.O. Licht, the West
German sugar statistical firm, that European sugar production will
increase from the 30.1 million tons produced last year to 32.3
million tons.
   Licht also said weather in the Soviet Union had been excellent,
resulting in an improved crop of sugar in that country, reducing its
import needs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Copper</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices continued their upward spiral as production
problems plagued producers worldwide while U.S. and Japanese demand
remained strong.
   As of July, U.S. rod and mill use of copper _ two-thirds of U.S.
copper consumption _ rose 10 percent from the year-earlier level,
analysts said.
   Besides a paralyzing strike in Peru, copper production is
hampered by a strike at the Highland Valley mines in British
Columbia, Canada; the bankruptcy of Mexico's Cananea mine which is
expected to be closed up to three months; and the shutdown of the
Bougainville, Papua New Guinea mine due to terrorist sabotage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Grain and Soybeans</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and Soybean futures contracts settled into a narrow trading
range as expectations for near normal harvest this fall become
stronger because of rainy weather in the Midwest.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Energy</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices struggled in a market that has been slow
all summer. Analysts and traders said uncertainty over the actual
demand for petroleum products in the second half of the year makes
the price outlook uncertain.
   A report from the Department of Energy showing a surprisingly
large increase in U.S. crude oil inventories did not help prices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Precious metals</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Trading in gold and silver remained slack due to a strong dollar
and little evidence of rising inflation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Livestock and meat</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle futures turned in a mixed performance as firm cash prices
weakened because of concerns over plentiful supplies. Pork futures
continued their steady gain on the strength of cash prices.
</TEXT>
