<HEAD>UNDATED: cash prices.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week.
   Grain futures were little changed and soybean futures were down
modestly on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat for September delivery settled at $3.90{ a bushel compared
to $3.92\ a week earlier; September corn fell to $2.32} a bushel
from $2.34}; September oats were dropped to $1.34} a bushel from
$1.38\; September soybeans plunged to $5.79{ a bushel from $5.84.
   Cattle futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange while
meat futures finished mixed.
   October live cattle fell to 75.27 cents a pound from 75.72 cents;
August feeder cattle dropped to 83.67 cents a pound from 84.57;
October live hogs were 41.32 cents a pound up from 41.05 cents;
February frozen pork bellies slipped to 41.62 cents a pound from
42.37 cents.
   Gold and silver futures dropped on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   August gold fell to $360.70 a troy ounce from $368.10; September
silver retreated to $5.115 a troy ounce from $5.255.
   Energy futures were mostly higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for September delivery fell to
$17.94 a barrel from $18.80; heating oil climbed to 51.43 cents a
gallon from 51.03 cents; unleaded gasoline rose to 53.30 cents a
gallon from 52.73 cents.
