<FIRST>d f PM-Stocks-Investors     08-26 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stocks-Investors,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Investors Returning To Stock Market, But Cautiously</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though some first-time investors who were scared
away by the stock market crash two years ago never returned, those
who remained got their reward, market watchers said.
   The record high of 2,734.64 in the Dow Jones industrials average
Thursday once again pointed out the value of a long-term investment
strategy, these observers said.
   On Friday, the average slipped back 2.28 points to 2,732.36.
   Anyone who held stocks for the past two years has about broken
even, while people who panicked and sold at the bottom took big
losses.
   ``A person has to live through a market break to fully appreciate
what can happen in the next market peak,'' said Ken Janke, president
of the National Association of Investors Corp., a non-profit group
of individual investors and investment-club members.
   Media accounts of small investors abandoning the stock market
after the crash were overblown, says James Cloonan, president of the
American Association of Individual Investors.
   The shrinkage in his members' stock portfolios was mainly from a
drop in the market price of shares, not stock sales, he said.
   Industry figures show that individual investors did leave the
market after the crash, but that many have since returned.
   According to the Securities Industry Association, an average of
37 million shares a day were traded by retail, as opposed to
institutional, customers on the New York Stock Exchange in August
1987.
   That November, after the crash, the average number of daily
retail trades dropped to 31 million. The average for all of 1988 was
29 million retail trades a day.
   But the figure jumped to 39 million a day from January to June of
this year, the latest figures available.
   ``The retail investor definitely is back,'' said George Monahan,
director of industry studies for the industry group.
   Nevertheless, Don Scidmore, a small investor in Seattle, said he
believes the Dow high could scare some investors away from the
market rather than lure new ones.
   ``The little investors, you can to go any (investment) club now
and they're chewing their fingers and saying the Dow's up now and
it's due for a fall,'' said Scidmore, who is retired and belongs to
two investment clubs.
   Scidmore is not frightened away himself. ``If you're in it for
the long run, so what?'' he said. ``It goes up and it goes down.''
   Individual investors feel unable to compete with market
professionals and institutions, said David McLaughlin, a portfolio
manager with Chase Investment Counsel Corp., an independent
financial consultant in Charlottesville, Va.
   ``The individual investor feels that he's sort of outside looking
in, that the experts know what's going on, they know where to look
for takeover candidates,'' McLaughlin said. ``The individual feels
that he doesn't get a fair shake.''
   McLaughlin believes the Dow high will do little to lure more
small investors back to the market. He said the reaction of many is,
``Well, I missed it and I should have been in on it but it's too
late now.''
   ``I think if we had a recession and we got into it for couple of
quarters, and of course the stock market would probably be lower,
then I think you'd see the individual investor coming back,'' he
said.
   On the flip side of that coin, McLaughlin said that if the Dow
continues its upward climb and sets more records, the trauma of the
crash could fade into the back of many investors' minds.
   Nancy Dunnan, an author of investment books, agreed that many
individual investors have returned to the market. But, she said,
``'87 wasn't that long ago, so you're not going to see all of them
jump back in.''
   She said small investors should have learned at least one lesson
from the crash.
   ``I think they should watch the market every single day and not
let it ride, and if they see a dip and they've already made their
profit to not be shy or greedy and take that profit,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
